1
00:00:00,004 --> 00:00:07,543
And next time I’ll have along a
gentle hawss for yu’.”

2
00:00:07,543 --> 00:00:10,063
“Next time!

3
00:00:10,063 --> 00:00:12,253
Next time!

4
00:00:12,253 --> 00:00:16,693
Well, perhaps I will go with you.

5
00:00:16,693 --> 00:00:18,613
Do you live far?”

6
00:00:18,613 --> 00:00:23,597
“I live on Judge Henry’s
ranch, over yondeh.”

7
00:00:23,597 --> 00:00:26,717
He pointed across the mountains.

8
00:00:26,717 --> 00:00:29,468
“It’s on Sunk Creek.

9
00:00:29,468 --> 00:00:35,268
A pretty rough trail;
but I can come hyeh to see you in

10
00:00:35,268 --> 00:00:40,557
a day, I reckon.

11
00:00:40,557 --> 00:00:51,174
Well, I hope you’ll cert’nly
enjoy good health, ma’am.”

12
00:00:51,174 --> 00:00:57,189
“Oh, there’s one thing!”

13
00:00:57,189 --> 00:01:01,980
said Molly Wood, calling
after him rather quickly.

14
00:01:01,980 --> 00:01:08,800
“I⁠—I’m not at all afraid of horses.

15
00:01:08,800 --> 00:01:12,853
You needn’t bring such a gentle one.

16
00:01:12,853 --> 00:01:20,275
I⁠—was very tired that day,
and⁠—and I don’t scream as a rule.”

17
00:01:20,275 --> 00:01:26,613
He turned and looked at her so that she
could not meet his glance.

18
00:01:26,613 --> 00:01:29,604
“Bless your heart!”

19
00:01:29,604 --> 00:01:31,857
said he.

20
00:01:31,857 --> 00:01:37,711
“Will yu’ give me one o’ those flowers?”

21
00:01:37,739 --> 00:01:40,270
“Oh, certainly!

22
00:01:40,270 --> 00:01:48,390
I’m always so glad when people like them.”

23
00:01:48,390 --> 00:01:54,988
“They’re pretty near the
color of your eyes.”

24
00:01:54,988 --> 00:01:57,508
“Never mind my eyes.”

25
00:01:57,508 --> 00:02:01,092
“Can’t help it, ma’am.

26
00:02:01,092 --> 00:02:03,207
Not since South Fork.”

27
00:02:03,207 --> 00:02:07,662
He put the flower in the leather band of
his hat, and rode away

28
00:02:07,662 --> 00:02:12,056
on his Monte horse.

29
00:02:12,056 --> 00:02:20,401
Miss Wood lingered a moment,
then made some steps toward her gate,

30
00:02:20,401 --> 00:02:29,382
from which he could still be seen;
and then, with something like a toss of

31
00:02:29,382 --> 00:02:36,356
the head, she went in and shut her door.

32
00:02:36,356 --> 00:02:45,442
Later in the day the Virginian met Mr.
McLean, who looked at his hat and

33
00:02:45,442 --> -1:59:59,000
innocently quoted, “ ‘My
Looloo picked a daisy.’

34
-1:59:59,000 --> 00:00:02,000
”

35
00:02:51,886 --> 00:02:56,102
“Don’t yu’, Lin,” said the Southerner.

36
00:02:56,102 --> 00:02:58,662
“Then I won’t,” said Lin.

37
00:02:58,662 --> 00:03:05,865
Thus, for this occasion,
did the Virginian part from his lady⁠—

38
00:03:05,865 --> 00:03:11,865
and nothing said one way or another about
the handkerchief that had disappeared

39
00:03:11,865 --> 00:03:15,455
during the South Fork incident.

40
00:03:15,455 --> 00:03:22,776
As we fall asleep at night,
our thoughts will often ramble back and

41
00:03:22,776 --> 00:03:26,748
forth between the two worlds.

42
00:03:26,748 --> 00:03:30,178
“What color were his eyes?”

43
00:03:30,178 --> 00:03:34,100
wondered Molly on her pillow.

44
00:03:34,100 --> 00:03:39,632
“His mustache is not bristly like
so many of them.

45
00:03:39,632 --> 00:03:45,232
Sam never gave me such a
look at Hoosic Junction.

46
00:03:45,232 --> 00:03:47,592
No.⁠ ⁠

47
00:03:47,592 --> 00:03:49,992
… You can’t come with me.⁠ ⁠

48
00:03:49,992 --> 00:03:52,552
… Get off your horse.⁠ ⁠

49
00:03:52,552 --> -1:59:59,000
… The passengers are all staring.⁠ ⁠

50
-1:59:59,000 --> 00:00:02,000
…”

51
00:03:58,992 --> 00:04:08,286
And while Molly was thus dreaming that
the Virginian had ridden his horse into

52
00:04:08,286 --> 00:04:16,257
the railroad car, and sat down beside
her, the fire in the great stone chimney

53
00:04:16,257 --> 00:04:24,978
of her cabin flickered quietly,
its gleams now and again touching the

54
00:04:24,978 --> 00:04:30,710
miniature of Grandmother
Stark upon the wall.

55
00:04:30,710 --> 00:04:37,350
Camped on the Sunk Creek trail,
the Virginian was telling

56
00:04:37,350 --> 00:04:40,911
himself in his blankets:⁠—

57
00:04:40,911 --> 00:04:43,271
“I ain’t too old for education.

58
00:04:43,271 --> 00:04:46,471
Maybe she will lend me books.

59
00:04:46,471 --> 00:04:52,773
And I’ll watch her ways and
learn⁠ ⁠… stand still, Monte.

60
00:04:52,773 --> 00:04:58,214
I can learn a lot more than
the kids on that.

61
00:04:58,214 --> -1:59:59,000
There’s Monte⁠

62
-1:59:59,000 --> 00:00:02,000
⁠…

63
00:04:59,924 --> 00:05:04,156
you pie-biter, stop.⁠ ⁠

64
00:05:04,156 --> -1:59:59,000
… He has ate up your book,
ma’am, but I’ll get yu’.⁠ ⁠

65
-1:59:59,000 --> 00:00:02,000
…”

66
00:05:11,936 --> 00:05:15,607
And then the Virginian was fast asleep.

67
00:05:15,607 --> 00:05:16,806
CHAPTER XII

68
00:05:16,806 --> 00:05:18,942
Quality and Equality

69
00:05:18,942 --> 00:05:26,877
To the circle at Bennington,
a letter from Bear Creek was always a

70
00:05:26,877 --> 00:05:36,954
welcome summons to gather and hear of
doings very strange to Vermont.

71
00:05:36,954 --> 00:05:41,765
And when the tale of the changed babies
arrived duly by the post,

72
00:05:41,765 --> 00:05:49,568
it created a more than usual sensation,
and was read to a large number of

73
00:05:49,568 --> 00:05:53,621
pleased and scandalized neighbors.

74
00:05:53,621 --> 00:05:59,282
“I hate her to be where such things can
happen,” said Mrs. Wood.

75
00:05:59,282 --> 00:06:09,267
“I wish I could have been there,”
said her son-in-law, Andrew Bell.

76
00:06:09,267 --> 00:06:19,948
“She does not mention who played the
trick,” said Mrs. Andrew Bell.

77
00:06:19,948 --> 00:06:26,049
“We shouldn’t be any wiser if she
did,” said Mrs. Wood.

78
00:06:26,049 --> 00:06:35,433
“I’d like to meet the
perpetrator,” said Andrew.

79
00:06:35,433 --> 00:06:38,364
“Oh, no!”

80
00:06:38,364 --> 00:06:41,333
said Mrs. Wood.

81
00:06:41,333 --> 00:06:45,818
“They’re all horrible.”

82
00:06:45,818 --> 00:06:52,700
And she wrote at once,
begging her daughter to take good care

83
00:06:52,700 --> 00:07:03,455
of herself, and to see as much of
Mrs. Balaam as possible.

84
00:07:03,455 --> 00:07:07,217
“And of any other ladies
that are near you.

85
00:07:07,217 --> 00:07:13,508
For you seem to me to be in
a community of roughs.

86
00:07:13,508 --> 00:07:17,246
I wish you would give it all up.

87
00:07:17,246 --> 00:07:24,627
Did you expect me to laugh
about the babies?”

88
00:07:24,627 --> 00:07:25,225
Mrs.

89
00:07:25,225 --> 00:07:33,579
Flynt, when this story was repeated to
her (she had not been invited in to hear

90
00:07:33,579 --> 00:07:39,231
the letter), remarked that she had
always felt that Molly Wood must be a

91
00:07:39,231 --> 00:07:46,544
little vulgar, ever since she began to
go about giving music lessons

92
00:07:46,544 --> 00:07:50,152
like any ordinary German.

93
00:07:50,152 --> 00:07:57,035
But Mrs. Wood was considerably relieved
when the next letter arrived.

94
00:07:57,035 --> 00:08:06,056
It contained nothing horrible
about barbecues or babies.

95
00:08:06,056 --> 00:08:14,287
It mentioned the great beauty of the
weather, and how well and strong the

96
00:08:14,287 --> 00:08:19,881
fine air was making the writer feel.

97
00:08:19,881 --> 00:08:26,621
And it asked that books might be sent,
many books of all sorts,

98
00:08:26,621 --> 00:08:36,053
novels, poetry, all the good old books
and any good new ones

99
00:08:36,053 --> 00:08:38,785
that could be spared.

100
00:08:38,785 --> 00:08:41,776
Cheap editions, of course.

101
00:08:41,776 --> 00:08:44,396
“Indeed she shall have them!”

102
00:08:44,396 --> 00:08:46,437
said Mrs. Wood.

103
00:08:46,437 --> 00:08:51,667
“How her mind must be starving
in that dreadful place!”

104
00:08:51,667 --> 00:08:58,960
The letter was not a long one,
and, besides the books,

105
00:08:58,960 --> 00:09:05,600
spoke of little else except the fine
weather and the chances for outdoor

106
00:09:05,600 --> 00:09:09,323
exercise that this gave.

107
00:09:09,323 --> 00:09:16,314
“You have no idea,” it said,
“how delightful it is to ride,

108
00:09:16,314 --> -1:59:59,000
especially on a spirited horse,
which I can do now quite well.

109
-1:59:59,000 --> 00:00:02,000
”

110
00:09:22,838 --> 00:09:24,238
“How nice that is!”

111
00:09:24,238 --> 00:09:28,549
said Mrs. Wood, putting down the letter.

112
00:09:28,549 --> 00:09:32,199
“I hope the horse is not too spirited.”

113
00:09:32,199 --> 00:09:35,753
“Who does she go riding with?”

114
00:09:35,753 --> 00:09:38,153
asked Mrs. Bell.

115
00:09:38,153 --> 00:09:40,833
“She doesn’t say, Sarah.

116
00:09:40,833 --> -1:59:59,000
Why?

117
-1:59:59,000 --> 00:00:02,000
”

118
00:09:42,206 --> 00:09:44,174
“Nothing.

119
00:09:44,174 --> 00:09:50,217
She has a queer way of not mentioning
things, now and then.”

120
00:09:50,217 --> 00:09:51,195
“Sarah!”

121
00:09:51,195 --> 00:09:56,445
exclaimed Mrs. Wood, reproachfully.

122
00:09:56,445 --> 00:10:03,425
“Oh, well, mother, you know just as well
as I do that she can be

123
00:10:03,425 --> 00:10:07,185
very independent and unconventional.”

124
00:10:07,185 --> 00:10:10,897
“Yes; but not in that way.

125
00:10:10,897 --> -1:59:59,000
She wouldn’t ride with poor Sam Bannett,
and after all he is a suitable person.

126
-1:59:59,000 --> 00:00:02,000
”

127
00:10:20,527 --> 00:10:31,609
Nevertheless, in her next letter,
Mrs. Wood cautioned her daughter about

128
00:10:31,609 --> 00:10:43,592
trusting herself with any one of whom
Mrs. Balaam did not thoroughly approve.

129
00:10:43,592 --> 00:11:01,820
The good lady could never grasp that Mrs.
Balaam lived a long day’s journey from

130
00:11:01,820 --> 00:11:08,460
Bear Creek, and that Molly saw her about
once every three months.

131
00:11:08,460 --> 00:11:17,569
“We have sent your books,”
the mother wrote; “everybody has

132
00:11:17,569 --> 00:11:22,479
contributed from their store⁠—
Shakespeare, Tennyson,

133
00:11:22,479 --> 00:11:27,046
Browning, Longfellow;
and a number of novels by Scott,

134
00:11:27,046 --> 00:11:33,346
Thackeray, George Eliot,
Hawthorne, and lesser writers;

135
00:11:33,346 --> 00:11:40,986
some volumes of Emerson;
and Jane Austen complete,

136
00:11:40,986 --> 00:11:45,790
because you admire her so particularly.”

137
00:11:45,790 --> 00:11:51,907
This consignment of literature reached
Bear Creek about a week

138
00:11:51,907 --> 00:11:54,907
before Christmas time.

139
00:11:54,907 --> 00:12:00,947
By New Year’s Day, the Virginian
had begun his education.

140
00:12:00,947 --> 00:12:07,177
“Well, I have managed to get through
’em,” he said, as he entered

141
00:12:07,177 --> 00:12:09,297
Molly’s cabin in February.

142
00:12:09,297 --> 00:12:13,337
And he laid two volumes upon her table.

143
00:12:13,337 --> 00:12:15,989
“And what do you think of them?”

144
00:12:15,989 --> 00:12:17,879
she inquired.

145
00:12:17,879 --> 00:12:24,139
“I think that I’ve cert’nly earned a
good long ride today.”

146
00:12:24,139 --> 00:12:28,799
“Georgie Taylor has sprained his ankle.”

147
00:12:28,799 --> 00:12:33,653
“No, I don’t mean that kind of a ride.

148
00:12:33,653 --> 00:12:40,458
I’ve earned a ride with just us two alone.

149
00:12:40,458 --> 00:12:45,674
I’ve read every word of both
of ’em, yu’ know.”

150
00:12:45,674 --> 00:12:48,114
“I’ll think about it.

151
00:12:48,114 --> 00:12:52,659
Did you like them?”

152
00:12:52,659 --> 00:12:53,839
“No.

153
00:12:53,839 --> 00:12:56,222
Not much.

154
00:12:56,222 --> 00:13:06,235
If I’d knowed that one was a detective
story, I’d have got yu’ to try

155
00:13:06,235 --> 00:13:09,475
something else on me.

156
00:13:09,475 --> 00:13:17,656
Can you guess the murderer,
or is the author too smart for yu’?

157
00:13:17,656 --> 00:13:20,216
That’s all they amount to.

158
00:13:20,216 --> 00:13:29,160
Well, he was too smart for me this time,
but that didn’t distress me any.

159
00:13:29,160 --> 00:13:34,460
That other book talks too much.”

160
00:13:34,460 --> -1:59:59,000
Molly was scandalized,
and she told him it was a great work.

161
-1:59:59,000 --> 00:00:02,000
“

162
00:13:46,314 --> 00:13:49,044
Oh, yes, yes.

163
00:13:49,044 --> 00:13:51,804
A fine book.

164
00:13:51,804 --> 00:13:59,067
But it will keep up its talkin’.

165
00:13:59,067 --> 00:14:01,361
Don’t let you alone.”

166
00:14:01,361 --> 00:14:07,419
“Didn’t you feel sorry
for poor Maggie Tulliver?”

167
00:14:07,419 --> 00:14:11,426
“Hmp.

168
00:14:11,480 --> 00:14:13,066
Yes.

169
00:14:13,066 --> 00:14:17,502
Sorry for her, and for Tawmmy, too.

170
00:14:17,502 --> 00:14:24,563
But the man did right to drownd ’em both.”

171
00:14:24,563 --> 00:14:26,774
“It wasn’t a man.

172
00:14:26,774 --> 00:14:29,014
A woman wrote that.”

173
00:14:29,014 --> 00:14:31,294
“A woman did!

174
00:14:31,294 --> 00:14:35,159
Well, then, o’ course she talks too much.”

175
00:14:35,159 --> 00:14:37,570
“I’ll not go riding with you!”

176
00:14:37,570 --> 00:14:38,503
shrieked Molly.

177
00:14:38,503 --> 00:14:39,420
But she did.

178
00:14:39,420 --> 00:14:44,432
And he returned to Sunk Creek,
not with a detective story,

179
00:14:44,432 --> 00:14:47,240
but this time with a Russian novel.

180
00:14:47,240 --> 00:14:51,719
It was almost April when he brought it
back to her⁠—and a heavy sleet storm

181
00:14:51,719 --> 00:14:53,029
lost them their ride.

182
00:14:53,029 --> 00:14:57,429
So he spent his time indoors with her,
not speaking a syllable of love.

183
00:14:57,429 --> 00:15:02,125
When he came to take his departure,
he asked her for some other book

184
00:15:02,125 --> 00:15:03,315
by this same Russian.

185
00:15:03,315 --> 00:15:05,518
But she had no more.

186
00:15:05,518 --> 00:15:07,233
“I wish you had,” he said.

187
00:15:07,233 --> 00:15:10,946
“I’ve never saw a book could tell the
truth like that one does.”

188
00:15:10,946 --> 00:15:13,017
“Why, what do you like about it?”

189
00:15:13,017 --> 00:15:14,537
she exclaimed.

190
00:15:14,537 --> 00:15:16,811
To her it had been distasteful.

191
00:15:16,811 --> 00:15:19,247
“Everything,” he answered.

192
00:15:19,247 --> 00:15:23,391
“That young come-outer,
and his fam’ly that can’t understand

193
00:15:23,391 --> 00:15:31,264
him⁠—for he is broad gauge,
yu’ see, and they are narro’ gauge.”

194
00:15:31,264 --> 00:15:34,853
The Virginian looked at Molly
a moment almost shyly.

195
00:15:34,853 --> 00:15:38,955
“Do you know,” he said,
and a blush spread over his face,

196
00:15:38,955 --> 00:15:43,626
“I pretty near cried when that young
come-outer was dyin’, and said about

197
00:15:43,626 --> 00:15:45,650
himself, ‘I was a giant.’

198
00:15:45,650 --> 00:15:50,044
Life made him broad gauge,
yu’ see, and then took his chance away.”

199
00:15:50,044 --> 00:15:53,876
Molly liked the Virginian for his blush.

200
00:15:53,876 --> 00:15:55,750
It made him very handsome.

201
00:15:55,750 --> 00:16:00,988
But she thought that it came from his
confession about “pretty near crying.”

202
00:16:00,988 --> 00:16:05,009
The deeper cause she failed
to divine⁠—that

203
00:16:05,009 --> 00:16:05,409
he

204
00:16:05,409 --> 00:16:10,402
, like the dying hero in the novel,
felt himself to be a giant whom life had

205
00:16:10,402 --> 00:16:12,982
made “broad gauge,” and
denied opportunity.

206
00:16:12,982 --> 00:16:19,637
Fecund nature begets and squanders
thousands of these rich seeds in

207
00:16:19,637 --> 00:16:21,318
the wilderness of life.

208
00:16:21,318 --> 00:16:24,317
He took away with him
a volume of Shakespeare.

209
00:16:24,317 --> 00:16:27,669
“I’ve saw good plays of his,” he remarked.

210
00:16:27,669 --> 00:16:32,960
Kind Mrs. Taylor in her cabin next door
watched him ride off in the sleet,

211
00:16:32,960 --> 00:16:34,865
bound for the lonely mountain trail.

212
00:16:34,865 --> 00:16:38,720
“If that girl don’t get ready to take him
pretty soon,” she observed to her

213
00:16:38,720 --> 00:16:41,328
husband, “I’ll give her a
piece of my mind.”

214
00:16:41,328 --> 00:16:42,896
Taylor was astonished.

215
00:16:42,896 --> 00:16:44,358
“Is he thinking of her?”

216
00:16:44,358 --> 00:16:45,411
he inquired.

217
00:16:45,411 --> 00:16:47,660
“Lord, Mr. Taylor, and why shouldn’t he?”

218
00:16:47,660 --> 00:16:50,991
Mr. Taylor scratched his head and
returned to his newspaper.

219
00:16:50,991 --> 00:16:55,161
It was warm⁠—warm and
beautiful upon Bear Creek.

220
00:16:55,161 --> 00:17:00,242
Snow shone upon the peaks of the Bow Leg
range; lower on their slopes the pines

221
00:17:00,242 --> 00:17:04,562
were stirring with a gentle song;
and flowers bloomed across the wide

222
00:17:04,562 --> 00:17:05,842
plains at their feet.

223
00:17:05,842 --> 00:17:11,025
Molly and her Virginian sat at a certain
spring where he had often

224
00:17:11,025 --> 00:17:11,914
ridden with her.

225
00:17:11,914 --> 00:17:17,458
On this day he was bidding her farewell
before undertaking the most important

226
00:17:17,458 --> 00:17:20,456
trust which Judge Henry had
as yet given him.

227
00:17:20,456 --> 00:17:25,259
For this journey she had provided him
with Sir Walter Scott’s Kenilworth.

228
00:17:25,259 --> 00:17:27,457
Shakespeare he had returned to her.

229
00:17:27,457 --> 00:17:29,995
He had bought Shakespeare for himself.

230
00:17:29,995 --> 00:17:33,949
“As soon as I got used to readin’ it,”
he had told her, “I knowed for certain

231
00:17:33,949 --> -1:59:59,000
that I liked readin’ for enjoyment.

232
-1:59:59,000 --> 00:00:02,000
”

233
00:17:35,873 --> 00:17:39,781
But it was not of books that he
had spoken much today.

234
00:17:39,781 --> 00:17:42,043
He had not spoken at all.

235
00:17:42,043 --> 00:17:48,215
He had bade her listen to the meadowlark,
when its song fell upon the silence like

236
00:17:48,215 --> 00:17:49,799
beaded drops of music.

237
00:17:49,799 --> 00:17:53,374
He had showed her where a covey of young
willow-grouse were hiding

238
00:17:53,374 --> 00:17:55,215
as their horses passed.

239
00:17:55,215 --> 00:17:59,818
And then, without warning,
as they sat by the spring,

240
00:17:59,818 --> 00:18:02,523
he had spoken potently of his love.

241
00:18:02,523 --> 00:18:04,729
She did not interrupt him.

242
00:18:04,729 --> 00:18:07,390
She waited until he was wholly finished.

243
00:18:07,390 --> 00:18:12,458
“I am not the sort of wife you want,”
she said, with an attempt of airiness.

244
00:18:12,458 --> 00:18:15,524
He answered roughly, “I am
the judge of that.”

245
00:18:15,524 --> 00:18:19,893
And his roughness was a pleasure to her,
yet it made her afraid of herself.

246
00:18:19,893 --> 00:18:23,693
When he was absent from her,
and she could sit in her cabin and look

247
00:18:23,693 --> 00:18:26,900
at Grandmother Stark,
and read home letters,

248
00:18:26,900 --> 00:18:31,717
then in imagination she found it easy to
play the part which she had arranged to

249
00:18:31,717 --> 00:18:35,957
play regarding him⁠—the part of the
guide, and superior,

250
00:18:35,957 --> 00:18:39,458
and indulgent companion.

251
00:18:39,458 --> 00:18:43,112
But when he was by her side,
that part became a difficult one.

252
00:18:43,112 --> 00:18:47,553
Her woman’s fortress was shaken by a
force unknown to her before.

253
00:18:47,553 --> 00:18:52,470
Sam Bannett did not have it in him to
look as this man could look,

254
00:18:52,470 --> 00:18:57,665
when the cold lustre of his eyes grew
hot with internal fire.

255
00:18:57,665 --> 00:19:00,077
What color they were baffled her still.

256
00:19:00,077 --> 00:19:02,306
“Can it possibly change?”

257
00:19:02,306 --> 00:19:03,057
she wondered.

258
00:19:03,057 --> 00:19:06,706
It seemed to her that sometimes when she
had been looking from a rock straight

259
00:19:06,706 --> 00:19:09,908
down into clear sea water,
this same color had lurked in its

260
00:19:09,908 --> 00:19:10,591
depths.

261
00:19:10,591 --> 00:19:13,420
“Is it green, or is it gray?”

262
00:19:13,420 --> 00:19:17,410
she asked herself, but did not turn
just now to see.

263
00:19:17,410 --> 00:19:19,910
She kept her face toward the landscape.

264
00:19:19,910 --> 00:19:23,733
“All men are born equal,”
he now remarked slowly.

265
00:19:23,733 --> 00:19:28,362
“Yes,” she quickly answered,
with a combative flash.

266
00:19:28,362 --> 00:19:28,985
“Well?”

267
00:19:28,985 --> 00:19:31,262
“Maybe that don’t include women?”

268
00:19:31,262 --> 00:19:32,138
he suggested.

269
00:19:32,138 --> 00:19:33,526
“I think it does.”

270
00:19:33,526 --> 00:19:35,369
“Do yu’ tell the kids so?”

271
00:19:35,369 --> 00:19:38,366
“Of course I teach them what I believe!”

272
00:19:38,366 --> 00:19:39,167
He pondered.

273
00:19:39,167 --> 00:19:45,174
“I used to have to learn about
the Declaration of Independence.

274
00:19:45,174 --> 00:19:48,004
I hated books and truck when I was a kid.”

275
00:19:48,004 --> 00:19:49,371
“But you don’t any more.”

276
00:19:49,371 --> 00:19:49,989
“No.

277
00:19:49,989 --> 00:19:51,638
I cert’nly don’t.

278
00:19:51,638 --> 00:19:57,461
But I used to get kep’ in at recess
for bein’ so dumb.

279
00:19:57,461 --> 00:20:02,426
I was most always at the tail
end of the class.

280
00:20:02,426 --> 00:20:04,937
My brother, he’d be head sometimes.”

281
00:20:04,937 --> 00:20:10,041
“Little George Taylor is my
prize scholar,” said Molly.

282
00:20:10,041 --> 00:20:12,031
“Knows his tasks, does he?”

283
00:20:12,031 --> 00:20:13,055
“Always.

284
00:20:13,055 --> 00:20:14,936
And Henry Dow comes next.”

285
00:20:14,936 --> 00:20:16,621
“Who’s last?”

286
00:20:16,621 --> 00:20:17,976
“Poor Bob Carmody.

287
00:20:17,976 --> 00:20:21,496
I spend more time on him than on all
the rest put together.”

288
00:20:21,496 --> 00:20:22,779
“My!”

289
00:20:22,779 --> 00:20:23,727
said the Virginian.

290
00:20:23,727 --> 00:20:25,098
“Ain’t that strange!”

291
00:20:25,098 --> 00:20:27,692
She looked at him, puzzled by his tone.

292
00:20:27,692 --> 00:20:30,709
“It’s not strange when you
know Bob,” she said.

293
00:20:30,709 --> 00:20:34,364
“It’s very strange,” drawled
the Virginian.

294
00:20:34,364 --> 00:20:38,931
“Knowin’ Bob don’t help it any.”

295
00:20:38,931 --> 00:20:43,258
“I don’t think that I understand
you,” said Molly, sticky.

296
00:20:43,258 --> 00:20:45,727
“Well, it is mighty confusin’.

297
00:20:45,727 --> 00:20:50,207
George Taylor, he’s your best scholar,
and poor Bob, he’s your worst,

298
00:20:50,207 --> 00:20:53,768
and there’s a lot in the middle⁠—and you
tell me we’re all born equal!”

299
00:20:53,768 --> 00:20:58,346
Molly could only sit giggling in this
trap he had so ingeniously laid for her.

300
00:20:58,346 --> 00:21:01,570
“I’ll tell you what,”
pursued the cowpuncher,

301
00:21:01,570 --> 00:21:07,062
with slow and growing intensity,
“equality is a great big bluff.

302
00:21:07,062 --> -1:59:59,000
It’s easy called.

303
-1:59:59,000 --> 00:00:02,000
”

304
00:21:08,772 --> 00:21:10,946
“I didn’t mean⁠—” began Molly.

305
00:21:10,946 --> 00:21:13,012
“Wait, and let me say what I mean.”

306
00:21:13,012 --> 00:21:15,574
He had made an imperious
gesture with his hand.

307
00:21:15,574 --> 00:21:18,733
“I know a man that mostly wins at cyards.

308
00:21:18,733 --> 00:21:21,236
I know a man that mostly loses.

309
00:21:21,236 --> 00:21:23,716
He says it is his luck.

310
00:21:23,716 --> 00:21:24,603
All right.

311
00:21:24,603 --> 00:21:26,053
Call it his luck.

312
00:21:26,053 --> 00:21:29,609
I know a man that works hard and he’s
gettin’ rich, and I know another that

313
00:21:29,609 --> 00:21:31,835
works hard and is gettin’ poor.

314
00:21:31,835 --> 00:21:33,557
He says it is his luck.

315
00:21:33,557 --> 00:21:34,702
All right.

316
00:21:34,702 --> 00:21:35,884
Call it his luck.

317
00:21:35,884 --> 00:21:40,624
I look around and I see folks movin’ up
or movin’ down, winners

318
00:21:40,624 --> 00:21:42,551
or losers everywhere.

319
00:21:42,551 --> 00:21:44,440
All luck, of course.

320
00:21:44,440 --> 00:21:47,996
But since folks can be born that
different in their luck,

321
00:21:47,996 --> 00:21:49,356
where’s your equality?

322
00:21:49,356 --> 00:21:50,715
No, seh!

323
00:21:50,715 --> 00:21:54,767
call your failure luck,
or call it laziness,

324
00:21:54,767 --> 00:21:59,711
wander around the words,
prospect all yu’ mind to,

325
00:21:59,711 --> 00:22:03,225
and yu’ll come out the same
old trail of inequality.”

326
00:22:03,225 --> 00:22:05,346
He paused a moment and looked at her.

327
00:22:05,346 --> 00:22:09,864
“Some holds four aces,”
he went on, “and some holds nothin’, and

328
00:22:09,864 --> 00:22:15,890
some poor fello’ gets the aces and no
show to play ’em; but a man has got to

329
00:22:15,890 --> 00:22:19,221
prove himself my equal
before I’ll believe him.”

330
00:22:19,221 --> 00:22:21,939
Molly sat gazing at him, silent.

331
00:22:21,939 --> 00:22:25,281
“I know what yu’ meant,”
he told her now, “by sayin’ you’re not

332
00:22:25,281 --> 00:22:26,568
the wife I’d want.

333
00:22:26,568 --> 00:22:29,029
But I am the kind that moves up.

334
00:22:29,029 --> -1:59:59,000
I am goin’ to be your best scholar

335
-1:59:59,000 --> -1:59:59,000
.

336
-1:59:59,000 --> 00:00:02,000
”

337
00:22:31,615 --> 00:22:34,589
He turned toward her,
and that fortress within

338
00:22:34,589 --> 00:22:36,172
her began to shake.

339
00:22:36,172 --> 00:22:37,796
“Don’t,” she murmured.

340
00:22:37,796 --> -1:59:59,000
“Don’t, please.

341
-1:59:59,000 --> 00:00:02,000
”

342
00:22:39,932 --> 00:22:41,043
“Don’t what?”

343
00:22:41,043 --> 00:22:43,220
“Why⁠—spoil this.”

344
00:22:43,220 --> 00:22:44,427
“Spoil it?”

345
00:22:44,427 --> 00:22:51,971
“These rides⁠—I don’t love you⁠—I can’t⁠—
but these rides are⁠—”

346
00:22:51,971 --> 00:22:54,102
“What are they?”

347
00:22:54,102 --> 00:22:55,606
“My greatest pleasure.

348
00:22:55,606 --> 00:22:56,302
There!

349
00:22:56,302 --> 00:23:00,023
And, please, I want them to go on so.”

350
00:23:00,023 --> 00:23:01,194
“Go on so!

351
00:23:01,194 --> 00:23:03,190
I don’t reckon yu’ know
what you’re sayin’.

352
00:23:03,190 --> 00:23:06,076
Yu’ might as well ask fruit to stay green.

353
00:23:06,076 --> 00:23:10,183
If the way we are now can keep bein’
enough for you, it can’t for me.

354
00:23:10,183 --> 00:23:11,913
A pleasure to you, is it?

355
00:23:11,913 --> 00:23:15,500
Well, to me it is⁠—I don’t know
what to call it.

356
00:23:15,500 --> 00:23:20,187
I come to yu’ and I hate it,
and I come again and I hate it,

357
00:23:20,187 --> 00:23:24,494
and I ache and grieve all over when I
go.

358
00:23:24,494 --> 00:23:25,564
No!

359
00:23:25,564 --> -1:59:59,000
You will have to think of some other way
than just invitin’ me to keep green.

360
-1:59:59,000 --> 00:00:02,000
”

361
00:23:31,205 --> 00:23:34,284
“If I am to see you⁠—” began the girl.

362
00:23:34,284 --> 00:23:36,025
“You’re not to see me.

363
00:23:36,025 --> 00:23:37,386
Not like this.

364
00:23:37,386 --> 00:23:40,506
I can stay away easier than
what I am doin’.”

365
00:23:40,506 --> 00:23:44,608
“Will you do me a favor, a great one?”

366
00:23:44,608 --> 00:23:46,702
said she, now.

367
00:23:46,702 --> 00:23:49,623
“Make it as impossible as you please!”

368
00:23:49,623 --> 00:23:53,196
he cried.

369
00:23:53,196 --> 00:23:55,500
He thought it was to be some action.

370
00:23:55,500 --> 00:23:57,134
“Go on coming.

371
00:23:57,134 --> 00:24:02,586
But don’t talk to me about⁠—don’t talk in
that way⁠—if you can help it.”

372
00:24:02,586 --> 00:24:05,154
He laughed out, not permitting
himself to swear.

373
00:24:05,154 --> 00:24:08,479
“But,” she continued,
“if you can’t help talking that way⁠—

374
00:24:08,479 --> 00:24:10,910
sometimes⁠—I promise I will listen.

375
00:24:10,910 --> 00:24:12,876
That is the only promise I make.”

376
00:24:12,876 --> 00:24:15,078
“That is a bargain,” he said.

377
00:24:15,078 --> 00:24:20,124
Then he helped her mount her horse,
restraining himself like a Spartan,

378
00:24:20,124 --> 00:24:22,039
and they rode home to her cabin.

379
00:24:22,039 --> 00:24:24,964
“You have made it pretty near
impossible,” he said,

380
00:24:24,964 --> 00:24:26,111
as he took his leave.

381
00:24:26,111 --> 00:24:29,759
“But you’ve been square today,
and I’ll show you I can be square

382
00:24:29,759 --> 00:24:30,759
when I come back.

383
00:24:30,759 --> 00:24:33,640
I’ll not do more than ask you if
your mind’s the same.

384
00:24:33,640 --> 00:24:36,751
And now I’ll not see you
for quite a while.

385
00:24:36,751 --> 00:24:38,599
I am going a long way.

386
00:24:38,599 --> 00:24:40,286
But I’ll be very busy.

387
00:24:40,286 --> 00:24:44,899
And bein’ busy always keeps me from
grievin’ too much about you.”

388
00:24:44,899 --> 00:24:46,249
Strange is woman!

389
00:24:46,249 --> 00:24:49,442
She would rather have heard some other
last remark than this.

390
00:24:49,442 --> -1:59:59,000
“Oh, very well

391
-1:59:59,000 --> 00:00:02,000
!”

392
00:24:51,499 --> 00:24:53,486
she said.

393
00:24:53,486 --> 00:24:54,836
“I’ll not miss you either.”

394
00:24:54,836 --> 00:24:56,022
He smiled at her.

395
00:24:56,022 --> 00:24:59,746
“I doubt if yu’ can help
missin’ me,” he remarked.

396
00:24:59,746 --> 00:25:03,948
And he was gone at once,
galloping on his Monte horse.

397
00:25:03,948 --> 00:25:06,988
Which of the two won a victory this day?

398
00:25:06,988 --> 00:25:08,148
CHAPTER XIII

399
00:25:08,148 --> 00:25:10,948
The Game and the Nation⁠—Act First

400
00:25:10,948 --> 00:25:12,878
There can be no doubt of this:⁠—

401
00:25:12,878 --> 00:25:18,967
All America is divided into two classes⁠—
the quality and the equality.

402
00:25:18,967 --> 00:25:22,967
The latter will always recognize the
former when mistaken for it.

403
00:25:22,967 --> 00:25:29,556
Both will be with us until our women
bear nothing but kings.

404
00:25:29,556 --> 00:25:33,983
It was through the Declaration of
Independence that we Americans

405
00:25:33,983 --> 00:25:37,819
acknowledged the eternal
inequality of man.

406
00:25:37,819 --> 00:25:42,369
For by it we abolished a
cut-and-dried aristocracy.

407
00:25:42,369 --> 00:25:47,877
We had seen little men artificially held
up in high places, and great men

408
00:25:47,877 --> 00:25:52,924
artificially held down in low places,
and our own justice-loving hearts

409
00:25:52,924 --> 00:25:55,485
abhorred this violence to human nature.

410
00:25:55,485 --> 00:26:02,025
Therefore, we decreed that every man
should thenceforth have equal liberty to

411
00:26:02,025 --> 00:26:03,705
find his own level.

412
00:26:03,705 --> 00:26:10,148
By this very decree we acknowledged and
gave freedom to true aristocracy,

413
00:26:10,148 --> 00:26:14,267
saying, “Let the best man
win, whoever he is.”

414
00:26:14,267 --> 00:26:15,940
Let the best man win!

415
00:26:15,940 --> 00:26:18,173
That is America’s word.

416
00:26:18,173 --> 00:26:21,082
That is true democracy.

417
00:26:21,082 --> 00:26:26,391
And true democracy and true aristocracy
are one and the same thing.

418
00:26:26,391 --> 00:26:31,274
If anybody cannot see this,
so much the worse for his eyesight.

419
00:26:31,274 --> 00:26:34,624
The above reflections occurred to me
before reaching Billings,

420
00:26:34,624 --> 00:26:39,835
Montana, some three weeks after I had
unexpectedly met the

421
00:26:39,835 --> 00:26:42,755
Virginian at Omaha, Nebraska.

422
00:26:42,755 --> 00:26:46,035
I had not known of that trust given to
him by Judge Henry, which

423
00:26:46,035 --> 00:26:47,386
was taking him East.

424
00:26:47,386 --> 00:26:51,466
I was looking to ride with him before
long among the clean hills of Sunk

425
00:26:51,466 --> 00:26:52,078
Creek.

426
00:26:52,078 --> 00:26:54,106
I supposed he was there.

427
00:26:54,106 --> 00:26:59,547
But I came upon him one morning in
Colonel Cyrus Jones’s eating palace.

428
00:26:59,547 --> 00:27:02,059
Did you know the palace?

429
00:27:02,059 --> 00:27:07,282
It stood in Omaha, near the trains,
and it was ten years old (which is

430
00:27:07,282 --> 00:27:10,772
middle-aged in Omaha) when
I first saw it.

431
00:27:10,772 --> 00:27:14,483
It was a shell of wood,
painted with golden emblems⁠—the

432
00:27:14,483 --> 00:27:18,793
steamboat, the eagle,
the Yosemite⁠—and a live bear ate

433
00:27:18,793 --> 00:27:21,033
gratuities at its entrance.

434
00:27:21,033 --> 00:27:27,516
Weather permitting, it opened upon the
world as a stage upon the audience.

435
00:27:27,516 --> 00:27:33,296
You sat in Omaha’s whole sight and dined,
while Omaha’s dust came and

436
00:27:33,296 --> 00:27:35,298
settled upon the refreshments.

437
00:27:35,298 --> 00:27:40,575
It is gone the way of the Indian and the
buffalo, for the West is growing old.

438
00:27:40,575 --> 00:27:44,013
You should have seen the
palace and sat there.

439
00:27:44,013 --> 00:27:49,506
In front of you passed rainbows of men⁠—
Chinese, Indian chiefs,

440
00:27:49,506 --> 00:27:56,429
Africans, General Miles,
younger sons, Austrian nobility,

441
00:27:56,429 --> 00:27:58,957
wide females in pink.

442
00:27:58,957 --> 00:28:02,791
Our continent drained
prismatically through Omaha once.

443
00:28:02,791 --> 00:28:07,591
So I was passing that way also,
walking for the sake of ventilation from

444
00:28:07,591 --> 00:28:12,737
a sleeping-car toward a bath,
when the language of Colonel Cyrus Jones

445
00:28:12,737 --> 00:28:13,453
came out to me.

446
00:28:13,453 --> 00:28:16,486
The actual colonel I had
never seen before.

447
00:28:16,486 --> 00:28:20,682
He stood at the rear of his palace in
gray flowery mustaches and a Confederate

448
00:28:20,682 --> 00:28:24,065
uniform, telling the wishes of his
guests to the cook through a hole.

449
00:28:24,065 --> 00:28:28,203
You always bought meal tickets at once,
else you became unwelcome.

450
00:28:28,203 --> 00:28:34,397
Guests here had foibles at times,
and a rapid exit was too easy.

451
00:28:34,397 --> 00:28:36,116
Therefore I bought a ticket.

452
00:28:36,116 --> 00:28:41,043
It was spring and summer since I had
heard anything like the colonel.

453
00:28:41,043 --> 00:28:44,739
The Missouri had not yet flowed into New
York dialect freely,

454
00:28:44,739 --> 00:28:48,073
and his vocabulary met me like the
breeze of the plains.

455
00:28:48,073 --> 00:28:52,050
So I went in to be fanned by it,
and there sat the Virginian

456
00:28:52,050 --> 00:28:54,376
at a table, alone.

457
00:28:54,376 --> 00:28:58,385
His greeting was up to the code of
indifference proper on the plains;

458
00:28:58,385 --> 00:29:01,881
but he presently remarked,
“I’m right glad to see somebody,”

459
00:29:01,881 --> 00:29:03,340
which was a good deal to say.

460
00:29:03,340 --> 00:29:07,132
“Them that comes hyeh,”
he observed next, “don’t eat.

461
00:29:07,132 --> 00:29:08,096
They feed.”

462
00:29:08,096 --> 00:29:10,994
And he considered the guests
with a sombre attention.

463
00:29:10,994 --> 00:29:14,808
“D’ yu’ reckon they find joyful digestion
in this swallo’-an’-get-out trough?”

464
00:29:14,808 --> 00:29:16,236
“What are you doing here, then?”

465
00:29:16,236 --> 00:29:16,910
said I.

466
00:29:16,910 --> 00:29:18,255
“Oh, pshaw!

467
00:29:18,255 --> 00:29:21,955
When yu’ can’t have what you choose,
yu’ just choose what you have.”

468
00:29:21,955 --> 00:29:23,438
And he took the bill-of-fare.

469
00:29:23,438 --> 00:29:26,725
I began to know that he had something on
his mind, so I did not

470
00:29:26,725 --> 00:29:27,872
trouble him further.

471
00:29:27,872 --> 00:29:31,567
Meanwhile he sat studying
the bill-of-fare.

472
00:29:31,567 --> 00:29:33,251
“Ever heard o’ them?”

473
00:29:33,251 --> 00:29:36,742
he inquired, shoving me
the spotted document.

474
00:29:36,742 --> 00:29:44,078
Most improbable dishes were there⁠—
salmis, canapés, suprêmes⁠—all perfectly

475
00:29:44,078 --> 00:29:46,718
spelt and absolutely transparent.

476
00:29:46,718 --> 00:29:51,599
It was the old trick of copying some
metropolitan menu to catch travellers of

477
00:29:51,599 --> 00:29:55,330
the third and last dimension of
innocence; and whenever this is done the

478
00:29:55,330 --> 00:30:00,172
food is of the third and last dimension
of awfulness, which the cowpuncher knew

479
00:30:00,172 --> 00:30:01,952
as well as anybody.

480
00:30:01,952 --> 00:30:05,125
“So they keep that up here still,” I said.

481
00:30:05,125 --> 00:30:06,929
“But what about them?”

482
00:30:06,929 --> 00:30:07,858
he repeated.

483
00:30:07,858 --> 00:30:13,348
His finger was at a special item,
Frogs’ legs à la Delmonico.

484
00:30:13,348 --> 00:30:15,586
“Are they true anywheres?”

485
00:30:15,586 --> 00:30:16,341
he asked.

486
00:30:16,341 --> 00:30:18,743
And I told him, certainly.

487
00:30:18,743 --> 00:30:23,294
I also explained to him about Delmonico
of New York and about

488
00:30:23,294 --> 00:30:25,007
Augustin of Philadelphia.

489
00:30:25,007 --> 00:30:29,855
“There’s not a little bit o’ use in lyin’
to me this mawnin’,” he said,

490
00:30:29,855 --> 00:30:31,335
with his engaging smile.

491
00:30:31,335 --> -1:59:59,000
“I ain’t goin’ to awdeh anything’s laigs

492
-1:59:59,000 --> -1:59:59,000
.

493
-1:59:59,000 --> 00:00:02,000
”

494
00:30:33,959 --> 00:30:38,939
“Well, I’ll see how he gets out of it,”
I said, remembering the odd Texas

495
00:30:38,939 --> 00:30:39,470
legend.

496
00:30:39,470 --> 00:30:44,299
(The traveller read the bill-of-fare,
you know, and called for a vol-au-vent.

497
00:30:44,299 --> 00:30:47,939
And the proprietor looked at the
traveller, and running a pistol into his

498
00:30:47,939 --> 00:30:51,615
ear, observed, “You’ll take hash.”)

499
00:30:51,615 --> 00:30:55,551
I was thinking of this and wondering what
would happen to me.

500
00:30:55,551 --> 00:30:57,629
So I took the step.

501
00:30:57,629 --> 00:30:59,450
“Wants frogs’ legs, does he?”

502
00:30:59,450 --> 00:31:01,360
shouted Colonel Cyrus Jones.

503
00:31:01,360 --> 00:31:05,924
He fixed his eye upon me,
and it narrowed to a slit.

504
00:31:05,924 --> 00:31:11,069
“Too many brain workers breakfasting
before yu’ came in, professor,” said he.

505
00:31:11,069 --> 00:31:14,433
“Missionary ate the last leg
off me just now.

506
00:31:14,433 --> 00:31:15,734
Brown the wheat!”

507
00:31:15,734 --> 00:31:21,152
he commanded, through the hole to the
cook, for someone had ordered hot cakes.

508
00:31:21,152 --> 00:31:24,674
“I’ll have fried aiggs,”
said the Virginian.

509
00:31:24,674 --> 00:31:27,381
“Cooked both sides.”

510
00:31:27,381 --> 00:31:28,981
“White wings!”

511
00:31:28,981 --> 00:31:30,705
sang the colonel through the hole.

512
00:31:30,705 --> 00:31:32,229
“Let ’em fly up and down.”

513
00:31:32,229 --> 00:31:34,772
“Coffee an’ no milk,” said the Virginian.

514
00:31:34,772 --> 00:31:36,526
“Draw one in the dark!”

515
00:31:36,526 --> 00:31:38,132
the colonel roared.

516
00:31:38,132 --> 00:31:41,005
“And beefsteak, rare.”

517
00:31:41,005 --> 00:31:44,776
“One slaughter in the pan,
and let the blood drip!”

518
00:31:44,776 --> 00:31:49,020
“I should like a glass of
water, please,” said I.

519
00:31:49,020 --> 00:31:51,143
The colonel threw me a look of pity.

520
00:31:51,143 --> 00:31:53,569
“One Missouri and ice for the professor!”

521
00:31:53,569 --> 00:31:54,580
he said.

522
00:31:54,580 --> 00:31:57,468
“That fello’s a right live
man,” commented the Virginian.

523
00:31:57,468 --> 00:32:00,374
But he seemed thoughtful.

524
00:32:00,374 --> 00:32:03,602
Presently he inquired,
“Yu’ say he was a foreigner,

525
00:32:03,602 --> 00:32:06,597
an’ learned fancy cookin’ to New Yawk?”

526
00:32:06,597 --> 00:32:08,465
That was this cowpuncher’s way.

527
00:32:08,465 --> 00:32:13,500
Scarcely ever would he let drop a thing
new to him until he had got from you

528
00:32:13,500 --> 00:32:16,250
your whole information about it.

529
00:32:16,250 --> 00:32:22,072
So I told him the history of Lorenzo
Delmonico and his pioneer work,

530
00:32:22,072 --> 00:32:25,612
as much as I knew, and
the Southerner listened intently.

531
00:32:25,612 --> 00:32:29,012
“Mighty inter-estin’,” he said⁠—“mighty.

532
00:32:29,012 --> 00:32:32,663
He could just take little old o’rn’ry
frawgs, and dandy ’em up

533
00:32:32,663 --> 00:32:34,024
to suit the bloods.

534
00:32:34,024 --> -1:59:59,000
Mighty inter

535
-1:59:59,000 --> 00:00:02,000
-

536
00:32:35,070 --> 00:32:35,675
estin’.

537
00:32:35,675 --> 00:32:39,837
I expaict, though, his cookin’ would give
an outraiged stomach to

538
00:32:39,837 --> 00:32:41,049
a plain-raised man.”

539
00:32:41,049 --> 00:32:45,350
“If you want to follow it up,”
said I, by way of a sudden experiment,

540
00:32:45,350 --> 00:32:48,051
“Miss Molly Wood might have some
book about French dishes.”

541
00:32:48,051 --> 00:32:52,900
But the Virginian did not turn a hair.

542
00:32:52,900 --> 00:32:55,624
“I reckon she wouldn’t,” he answered.

543
00:32:55,624 --> 00:32:58,095
“She was raised in Vermont.

544
00:32:58,095 --> 00:33:01,550
They don’t bother overly about their
eatin’ up in Vermont.

545
00:33:01,550 --> 00:33:05,257
Hyeh’s what Miss Wood recommended the
las’ time I was seein’ her,”

546
00:33:05,257 --> 00:33:08,822
the cowpuncher added,
bringing Kenilworth from his pocket.

547
00:33:08,822 --> 00:33:10,822
“Right fine story.

548
00:33:10,822 --> -1:59:59,000
That Queen Elizabeth must have cert’nly
been a competent woman.

549
-1:59:59,000 --> 00:00:02,000
”

550
00:33:15,944 --> 00:33:19,970
“She was,” said I.

551
00:33:19,970 --> 00:33:22,198
But talk came to an end here.

552
00:33:22,198 --> 00:33:28,524
A dusty crew, most evidently from the
plains, now entered and drifted to a

553
00:33:28,524 --> 00:33:32,203
table; and each man of them gave the
Virginian about a quarter

554
00:33:32,203 --> 00:33:33,674
of a slouchy nod.

555
00:33:33,674 --> 00:33:35,958
His greeting to them was very serene.

556
00:33:35,958 --> 00:33:45,677
Only, Kenilworthwent back into his
pocket, and he breakfasted in silence.

557
00:33:45,677 --> 00:33:50,414
Among those who had greeted him I
now recognized a face.

558
00:33:50,414 --> 00:33:54,339
“Why, that’s the man you played cards
with at Medicine Bow!”

559
00:33:54,339 --> 00:33:54,957
I said.

560
00:33:54,957 --> 00:33:55,979
“Yes.

561
00:33:55,979 --> 00:33:57,350
Trampas.

562
00:33:57,350 --> 00:33:59,084
He’s got a job at the ranch now.”

563
00:33:59,084 --> 00:34:03,494
The Virginian said no more,
but went on with his breakfast.

564
00:34:03,494 --> 00:34:05,595
His appearance was changed.

565
00:34:05,595 --> 00:34:09,515
Aged I would scarcely say,
for this would seem as if he

566
00:34:09,515 --> 00:34:10,684
did not look young.

567
00:34:10,684 --> 00:34:14,884
But I think that the boy was altogether
gone from his face⁠—the boy whose freak

568
00:34:14,884 --> 00:34:19,787
with Steve had turned Medicine Bow
upside down, whose other freak with the

569
00:34:19,787 --> 00:34:23,667
babies had outraged Bear Creek,
the boy who had loved

570
00:34:23,667 --> 00:34:26,348
to jingle his spurs.

571
00:34:26,348 --> 00:34:30,983
But manhood had only trained,
not broken, his youth.

572
00:34:30,983 --> 00:34:35,185
It was all there, only obedient to
the rein and curb.

573
00:34:35,185 --> 00:34:38,632
Presently we went together
to the railway yard.

574
00:34:38,632 --> 00:34:41,740
“The Judge is doing a right smart o’
business this year,”

575
00:34:41,740 --> 00:34:46,209
he began, very casually indeed,
so that I knew this was important.

576
00:34:46,209 --> 00:34:51,727
Besides bells and coal smoke,
the smell and crowded sounds of cattle

577
00:34:51,727 --> 00:34:54,139
rose in the air around us.

578
00:34:54,139 --> 00:34:59,145
“Hyeh’s our first gather o’ beeves on the
ranch,” continued the Virginian.

579
00:34:59,145 --> 00:35:03,352
“The whole lot’s shipped through to
Chicago in two sections

580
00:35:03,352 --> 00:35:04,703
over the Burlington.

581
00:35:04,703 --> 00:35:06,681
The Judge is fighting the Elkhorn road.”

582
00:35:06,681 --> 00:35:11,755
We passed slowly along the two trains⁠—
twenty cars, each car packed with

583
00:35:11,755 --> 00:35:14,355
huddled, round-eyed, gazing steers.

584
00:35:14,355 --> 00:35:16,751
He examined to see if
any animals were down.

585
00:35:16,751 --> 00:35:21,277
“They ain’t ate or drank anything to
speak of,” he said, while the terrified

586
00:35:21,277 --> 00:35:23,586
brutes stared at us through their slats.

587
00:35:23,586 --> 00:35:27,673
“Not since they struck the
railroad they’ve not drank.

588
00:35:27,673 --> 00:35:32,619
Yu’ might suppose they know somehow what
they’re travellin’ to Chicago for.”

589
00:35:32,619 --> 00:35:36,374
And casually, always casually,
he told me the rest.

590
00:35:36,374 --> 00:35:42,500
Judge Henry could not spare his foreman
away from the second gather of beeves.

591
00:35:42,500 --> 00:35:47,718
Therefore these two ten-car trains with
their double crew of cowboys had been

592
00:35:47,718 --> 00:35:49,908
given to the Virginian’s charge.

593
00:35:49,908 --> 00:35:54,082
After Chicago, he was to return by St.

594
00:35:54,082 --> 00:35:56,965
Paul over the Northern Pacific;
for the Judge had wished him to see

595
00:35:56,965 --> 00:36:02,050
certain of the road’s directors and
explain to them persuasively how good a

596
00:36:02,050 --> 00:36:07,633
thing it would be for them to allow
especially cheap rates to the

597
00:36:07,633 --> 00:36:10,393
Sunk Creek outfit henceforth.

598
00:36:10,393 --> 00:36:13,735
This was all the Virginian told me;
and it contained the whole

599
00:36:13,735 --> 00:36:15,852
matter, to be sure.

600
00:36:15,852 --> 00:36:18,340
“So you’re acting foreman,” said I.

601
00:36:18,340 --> 00:36:21,621
“Why, somebody has to have
the say, I reckon.”

602
00:36:21,621 --> 00:36:24,660
“And of course you hated the promotion?”

603
00:36:24,660 --> 00:36:27,975
“I don’t know about promotion,”
he replied.

604
00:36:27,975 --> 00:36:31,001
“The boys have been used to seein’
me one of themselves.

605
00:36:31,001 --> 00:36:33,531
Why don’t you come along with
us far as Plattsmouth?”

606
00:36:33,531 --> 00:36:37,786
Thus he shifted the subject from himself,
and called to my notice the locomotives

607
00:36:37,786 --> 00:36:43,324
backing up to his cars,
and reminded me that from Plattsmouth I

608
00:36:43,324 --> 00:36:45,604
had the choice of two trains returning.

609
00:36:45,604 --> 00:36:51,088
But he could not hide or belittle this
confidence of his employer in him.

610
00:36:51,088 --> 00:36:54,624
It was the care of several thousand
perishable dollars and

611
00:36:54,624 --> 00:36:55,923
the control of men.

612
00:36:55,923 --> 00:36:57,487
It was a compliment.

613
00:36:57,487 --> 00:37:01,847
There were more steers than men to be
responsible for; but none of the steers

614
00:37:01,847 --> 00:37:06,405
had been suddenly picked from the herd
and set above his fellows.

615
00:37:06,405 --> 00:37:11,899
Moreover, Chicago finished up the steers;
but the new-made deputy foreman had then

616
00:37:11,899 --> 00:37:17,571
to lead his six highly unoccupied
brethren away from towns,

617
00:37:17,571 --> 00:37:21,670
and back in peace to the ranch,
or disappoint the Judge,

618
00:37:21,670 --> 00:37:23,566
who needed their services.

619
00:37:23,566 --> 00:37:28,049
These things sometimes go wrong in a land
where they say you are all born equal;

620
00:37:28,049 --> 00:37:32,125
and that quarter of a nod in Colonel
Cyrus Jones’s eating palace held more

621
00:37:32,125 --> 00:37:35,162
equality than any whole
nod you could see.

622
00:37:35,162 --> 00:37:39,441
But the Virginian did not see it,
there being a time for all things.

623
00:37:39,441 --> 00:37:43,048
We trundled down the flopping,
heavy-eddied Missouri to Plattsmouth,

624
00:37:43,048 --> 00:37:46,999
and there they backed us on to a siding,
the Christian Endeavor being expected

625
00:37:46,999 --> 00:37:48,145
to pass that way.

626
00:37:48,145 --> 00:37:53,203
And while the equality absorbed
themselves in a deep but harmless game

627
00:37:53,203 --> 00:37:57,995
of poker by the side of the railway
line, the Virginian and I sat on the top

628
00:37:57,995 --> 00:38:01,716
of a car, contemplating the sandy
shallows of the Platte.

629
00:38:01,716 --> 00:38:05,032
“I should think you’d take
a hand,” said I.

630
00:38:05,032 --> 00:38:06,107
“Poker?

631
00:38:06,107 --> 00:38:07,896
With them kittens?”

632
00:38:07,896 --> 00:38:12,343
One flash of the inner man lightened in
his eyes and died away,

633
00:38:12,343 --> 00:38:15,785
and he finished with his gentle drawl,
“When I play, I want

634
00:38:15,785 --> 00:38:16,833
it to be interestin’.”

635
00:38:16,833 --> 00:38:23,299
He took out Sir Walter’s Kenilworth once
more, and turned the volume over and

636
00:38:23,299 --> 00:38:26,023
over slowly, without opening it.

637
00:38:26,023 --> 00:38:31,808
You cannot tell if in spirit he wandered
on Bear Creek with the girl

638
00:38:31,808 --> 00:38:33,120
whose book it was.

639
00:38:33,120 --> 00:38:37,426
The spirit will go one road,
and the thought another,

640
00:38:37,426 --> 00:38:41,160
and the body its own way sometimes.

641
00:38:41,160 --> 00:38:45,619
“Queen Elizabeth would have played a
mighty pow’ful game,”

642
00:38:45,619 --> 00:38:47,145
was his next remark.

643
00:38:47,145 --> 00:38:47,819
“Poker?”

644
00:38:47,819 --> -1:59:59,000
said I.

645
-1:59:59,000 --> 00:00:02,000
“

646
00:38:48,555 --> 00:38:50,839
Yes, seh.

647
00:38:50,839 --> 00:38:54,619
Do you expaict Europe has got any queen
equal to her at present?”

648
00:38:54,619 --> 00:38:55,516
I doubted it.

649
00:38:55,516 --> 00:39:00,221
“Victoria’d get pretty nigh slain sliding
chips out agaynst Elizabeth.

650
00:39:00,221 --> 00:39:05,018
Only mos’ prob’ly Victoria she’d insist
on a half-cent limit.

651
00:39:05,018 --> 00:39:08,137
You have read this hyeh Kenilworth?

652
00:39:08,137 --> 00:39:13,605
Well, deal Elizabeth ace high,
an’ she could scare Robert Dudley with a

653
00:39:13,605 --> 00:39:16,061
full house plumb out o’ the bettin’.”

654
00:39:16,061 --> 00:39:19,806
I said that I believed
she unquestionably could.

655
00:39:19,806 --> 00:39:24,791
“And,” said the Virginian,
“if Essex’s play got next her too near,

656
00:39:24,791 --> 00:39:27,234
I reckon she’d have stacked the cyards.

657
00:39:27,234 --> -1:59:59,000
Say, d’ yu’ remember Shakespeare’s
fat man?

658
-1:59:59,000 --> 00:00:02,000
”

659
00:39:30,633 --> 00:39:31,394
“Falstaff?

660
00:39:31,394 --> 00:39:33,274
Oh, yes, indeed.”

661
00:39:33,274 --> 00:39:35,451
“Ain’t that grand?

662
00:39:35,451 --> 00:39:39,128
Why, he makes men talk the way
they do in life.

663
00:39:39,128 --> 00:39:41,300
I reckon he couldn’t get printed today.

664
00:39:41,300 --> 00:39:44,712
It’s a right down shame Shakespeare
couldn’t know about poker.

665
00:39:44,712 --> 00:39:49,449
He’d have had Falstaff playing all day
at that Tearsheet outfit.

666
00:39:49,449 --> -1:59:59,000
And the Prince would have beat him.

667
-1:59:59,000 --> 00:00:02,000
”

668
00:39:52,811 --> 00:39:56,866
“The Prince had the brains,” said I.

669
00:39:56,866 --> 00:39:58,403
“Brains?”

670
00:39:58,403 --> 00:39:59,382
“Well, didn’t he?”

671
00:39:59,382 --> 00:40:01,053
“I neveh thought to notice.

672
00:40:01,053 --> 00:40:02,443
Like as not he did.”

673
00:40:02,443 --> 00:40:04,483
“And Falstaff didn’t, I suppose?”

674
00:40:04,483 --> 00:40:05,432
“Oh, yes, seh!

675
00:40:05,432 --> 00:40:06,988
Falstaff could have played whist.”

676
00:40:06,988 --> 00:40:11,363
“I suppose you know what you’re talking
about; I don’t,” said I,

677
00:40:11,363 --> 00:40:12,643
for he was drawling again.

678
00:40:12,643 --> 00:40:16,900
The cowpuncher’s eye rested a
moment amiably upon me.

679
00:40:16,900 --> 00:40:23,445
“You can play whist with your brains,”
he mused⁠—“brains and cyards.

680
00:40:23,445 --> 00:40:26,725
Now cyards are only one o’ the
manifestations of poker

681
00:40:26,725 --> 00:40:28,229
in this hyeh world.

682
00:40:28,229 --> 00:40:33,611
One o’ the shapes yu fool with it in when
the day’s work is oveh.

683
00:40:33,611 --> 00:40:38,216
If a man is built like that Prince boy
was built (and it’s away down deep

684
00:40:38,216 --> 00:40:42,732
beyond brains), he’ll play winnin’ poker
with whatever hand he’s holdin’

685
00:40:42,732 --> 00:40:44,414
when the trouble begins.

686
00:40:44,414 --> 00:40:49,278
Maybe it will be a mean,
triflin’ army, or an empty six-shooter,

687
00:40:49,278 --> 00:40:54,882
or a lame hawss, or maybe just nothin’
but his natural countenance.

688
00:40:54,882 --> 00:40:59,117
’Most any old thing will do for a fello’
like that Prince boy to play poker

689
00:40:59,117 --> 00:41:00,237
with.”

690
00:41:00,237 --> 00:41:05,580
“Then I’d be grateful for your definition
of poker,” said I.

691
00:41:05,580 --> 00:41:09,613
Again the Virginian looked
me over amiably.

692
00:41:09,613 --> 00:41:13,741
“You put up a mighty pretty game o’
whist yourself,” he remarked.

693
00:41:13,741 --> 00:41:16,000
“Don’t that give you the
contented spirit?”

694
00:41:16,000 --> 00:41:20,457
And before I had any reply to this,
the Christian Endeavor began to

695
00:41:20,457 --> 00:41:21,747
come over the bridge.

696
00:41:21,747 --> 00:41:25,297
Three instalments crossed the Missouri
from Pacific Junction,

697
00:41:25,297 --> 00:41:29,771
bound for Pike’s Peak,
every car swathed in bright bunting,

698
00:41:29,771 --> 00:41:35,813
and at each window a Christian with
a handkerchief, joyously shrieking.

699
00:41:35,813 --> 00:41:40,508
Then the cattle trains got the open
signal, and I jumped off.

700
00:41:40,508 --> 00:41:45,423
“Tell the Judge the steers was all right
this far,” said the Virginian.

701
00:41:45,423 --> 00:41:48,278
That was the last of the deputy
foreman for a while.

702
00:41:48,278 --> 00:41:49,428
CHAPTER XIV

703
00:41:49,428 --> 00:41:51,212
Between the Acts

704
00:41:51,212 --> 00:41:54,934
My road to Sunk Creek lay
in no straight line.

705
00:41:54,934 --> 00:41:59,409
By rail I diverged northwest to
Fort Meade, and thence

706
00:41:59,409 --> 00:42:04,626
, after some stay with the kind military
people, I made my way on a horse.

707
00:42:04,626 --> 00:42:11,195
Up here in the Black Hills it
sluiced rain most intolerably.

708
00:42:11,195 --> 00:42:15,022
The horse and I enjoyed the country and
ourselves but little;

709
00:42:15,022 --> 00:42:19,368
and when finally I changed from the
saddle into a stagecoach,

710
00:42:19,368 --> 00:42:24,299
I caught a thankful expression upon the
animal’s face, and returned the same.

711
00:42:24,299 --> 00:42:28,095
“Six legs inside this jerky tonight?”

712
00:42:28,095 --> 00:42:30,574
said somebody, as I climbed the wheel.

713
00:42:30,574 --> 00:42:33,850
“Well, we’ll give thanks for not havin’
eight,” he added cheerfully.

714
00:42:33,850 --> 00:42:36,311
“Clamp your mind on to that, Shorty.”

715
00:42:36,311 --> 00:42:38,275
And he slapped the shoulder
of his neighbor.

716
00:42:38,275 --> 00:42:41,634
Naturally I took these
two for old companions.

717
00:42:41,634 --> 00:42:44,023
But we were all total strangers.

718
00:42:44,023 --> 00:42:48,783
They told me of the new gold excitement
at Rawhide, and supposed it would bring

719
00:42:48,783 --> 00:42:52,863
up the Northern Pacific;
and when I explained the millions owed

720
00:42:52,863 --> 00:42:57,504
to this road’s German bondholders,
they were of opinion that a German would

721
00:42:57,504 --> 00:42:59,568
strike it richer at Rawhide.

722
00:42:59,568 --> 00:43:03,334
We spoke of all sorts of things,
and in our silence I gloated on the

723
00:43:03,334 --> 00:43:07,029
autumn holiday promised
me by Judge Henry.

724
00:43:07,029 --> 00:43:10,468
His last letter had said that an outfit
would be starting for his ranch from

725
00:43:10,468 --> 00:43:13,415
Billings on the seventh,
and he would have a horse for me.

726
00:43:13,415 --> 00:43:14,765
This was the fifth.

727
00:43:14,765 --> 00:43:19,405
So we six legs in the jerky travelled
harmoniously on over the rain-gutted

728
00:43:19,405 --> 00:43:22,806
road, getting no deeper knowledge of
each other than what

729
00:43:22,806 --> 00:43:25,207
our outsides might imply.

730
00:43:25,207 --> 00:43:27,993
Not that we concealed anything.

731
00:43:27,993 --> 00:43:33,078
The man who had slapped
Shorty introduced himself early.

732
00:43:33,078 --> 00:43:35,546
“Scipio le Moyne, from
Gallipolice, Ohio,” he said.

733
00:43:35,546 --> 00:43:38,318
“The eldest of us always
gets called Scipio.

734
00:43:38,318 --> 00:43:39,224
It’s French.

735
00:43:39,224 --> 00:43:42,170
But us folks have been white
for a hundred years.”

736
00:43:42,170 --> 00:43:47,671
He was limber and light-muscled,
and fell skilfully about,

737
00:43:47,671 --> 00:43:51,803
evading bruises when the jerky reeled
or rose on end.

738
00:43:51,803 --> 00:43:57,400
He had a strange, long,
jocular nose, very wary-looking,

739
00:43:57,400 --> 00:43:59,205
and a bleached blue eye.

740
00:43:59,205 --> 00:44:03,093
Cattle was his business,
as a rule, but of late he had been

741
00:44:03,093 --> 00:44:06,607
“looking around some,”
and Rawhide seemed much on his brain.

742
00:44:06,607 --> 00:44:10,783
Shorty struck me as “looking around” also.

743
00:44:10,783 --> 00:44:14,337
He was quite short, indeed,
and the jerky hurt him almost every

744
00:44:14,337 --> 00:44:15,297
time.

745
00:44:15,297 --> 00:44:18,161
He was light-haired and mild.

746
00:44:18,161 --> 00:44:23,673
Think of a yellow dog that is lost,
and fancies each newcomer in sight is

747
00:44:23,673 --> 00:44:27,753
going to turn out his master,
and you will have Shorty.

748
00:44:27,753 --> 00:44:32,557
It was the Northern Pacific that
surprised us into intimacy.

749
00:44:32,557 --> 00:44:33,917
We were nearing Medora.

750
00:44:33,917 --> 00:44:37,439
We had made a last arrangement
of our legs.

751
00:44:37,439 --> 00:44:41,051
I lay stretched in silence,
placid in the knowledge it

752
00:44:41,051 --> 00:44:42,416
was soon to end.

753
00:44:42,416 --> 00:44:44,677
So I drowsed.

754
00:44:44,677 --> 00:44:49,402
I felt something sudden,
and, waking, saw Scipio

755
00:44:49,402 --> 00:44:51,287
passing through the air.

756
00:44:51,287 --> 00:44:55,690
As Shorty next shot from the jerky,
I beheld smoke and the locomotive.

757
00:44:55,690 --> 00:44:58,704
The Northern Pacific had
changed its schedule.

758
00:44:58,704 --> 00:45:03,335
A valise is a poor companion for
catching a train with.

759
00:45:03,335 --> 00:45:09,503
There was rutted sand and lumpy,
knee-high grease wood in our shortcut.

760
00:45:09,503 --> 00:45:15,614
A piece of stray wire sprang from some
hole and hung caracoling about my ankle.

761
00:45:15,614 --> 00:45:17,886
Tin cans spun from my stride.

762
00:45:17,886 --> 00:45:23,768
But we made a conspicuous race.

763
00:45:23,768 --> 00:45:28,461
Two of us waved hats,
and there was no moment that some one of

764
00:45:28,461 --> 00:45:29,902
us was not screeching.

765
00:45:29,902 --> 00:45:33,610
It meant twenty-four hours to us.

766
00:45:33,610 --> 00:45:36,688
Perhaps we failed to catch the train’s
attention, though the

767
00:45:36,688 --> 00:45:39,741
theory seems monstrous.

768
00:45:39,741 --> 00:45:44,337
As it moved off in our faces,
smooth and easy and insulting,

769
00:45:44,337 --> 00:45:48,824
Scipio dropped instantly to a walk,
and we two others outstripped him and

770
00:45:48,824 --> 00:45:50,762
came desperately to the empty track.

771
00:45:50,762 --> 00:45:52,190
There went the train.

772
00:45:52,190 --> 00:45:57,831
Even still its puffs were the separated
puffs of starting, that bitten-off,

773
00:45:57,831 --> 00:46:04,484
snorty kind, and sweat and our true
natures broke freely forth.

774
00:46:04,484 --> 00:46:08,563
I kicked my valise, and then
sat on it, dumb.

775
00:46:08,563 --> 00:46:11,525
Shorty yielded himself up aloud.

776
00:46:11,525 --> 00:46:13,600
All his humble secrets came out of him.

777
00:46:13,600 --> 00:46:16,725
He walked aimlessly round, lamenting.

778
00:46:16,725 --> 00:46:19,644
He had lost his job, and
he mentioned the ranch.

779
00:46:19,644 --> 00:46:22,401
He had played cards, and
he mentioned the man.

780
00:46:22,401 --> 00:46:25,857
He had sold his horse and saddle to catch
a friend on this train,

781
00:46:25,857 --> 00:46:28,396
and he mentioned what the friend had
been going to do for him.

782
00:46:28,396 --> 00:46:33,169
He told a string of griefs and names to
the air, as if the air knew.

783
00:46:33,169 --> 00:46:37,893
Meanwhile Scipio arrived with extreme
leisure at the rails.

784
00:46:37,893 --> 00:46:42,872
He stuck his hands into his pockets and
his head out at the very small train.

785
00:46:42,872 --> 00:46:49,674
His bleached blue eyes shut to slits as
he watched the rear car in its smoke-

786
00:46:49,674 --> 00:46:55,823
blur ooze away westward
among the mounded bluffs.

787
00:46:55,823 --> 00:46:58,109
“Lucky it’s out of range,” I thought.

788
00:46:58,109 --> 00:47:00,861
But now Scipio spoke to it.

789
00:47:00,861 --> 00:47:05,869
“Why, you seem to think you’ve left me
behind,” he began easily,

790
00:47:05,869 --> 00:47:07,328
in fawning tones.

791
00:47:07,328 --> 00:47:10,947
“You’re too much of a kid
to have such thoughts.

792
00:47:10,947 --> 00:47:11,865
Age some.”

793
00:47:11,865 --> 00:47:14,941
His next remark grew less wheedling.

794
00:47:14,941 --> 00:47:17,190
“I wouldn’t be a bit proud to meet yu’.

795
00:47:17,190 --> 00:47:22,722
Why, if I was seen travellin’ with yu’,
I’d have to explain it to my friends!

796
00:47:22,722 --> 00:47:24,288
Think you’ve got me left, do yu’?

797
00:47:24,288 --> 00:47:28,931
Just because yu’ ride through this
country on a rail, do yu’ claim yu’ can

798
00:47:28,931 --> 00:47:30,531
find your way around?

799
00:47:30,531 --> 00:47:35,046
I could take yu’ out ten yards in the
brush and lose yu’ in ten seconds,

800
00:47:35,046 --> 00:47:35,206
you spangle-roofed hobo!

801
00:47:35,206 --> 00:47:35,615
Leave me behind?

802
00:47:35,615 --> 00:47:39,239
you recent blanket-mortgage yearlin’!

803
00:47:39,239 --> 00:47:43,363
You plush-lined, nickel-plated,
whistlin’ wash room,

804
00:47:43,363 --> 00:47:47,586
d’ yu’ figure I can’t go east just
as soon as west?

805
00:47:47,586 --> 00:47:51,840
Or I’ll stay right here if it suits me,
yu’ dude-inhabited hotbox!

806
00:47:51,840 --> 00:47:54,849
Why, yu’ coon-bossed face-towel⁠—”

807
00:47:54,849 --> 00:48:00,007
But from here he rose in flights of
novelty that appalled and held me

808
00:48:00,007 --> 00:48:02,660
spellbound, and which are not for me
to say to you.

809
00:48:02,660 --> 00:48:06,207
Then he came down easily again,
and finished with expressions of

810
00:48:06,207 --> 00:48:09,527
sympathy for it because it could never
have known a mother.

811
00:48:09,527 --> 00:48:13,471
“Do you expaict it could show
a male parent offhand?”

812
00:48:13,471 --> 00:48:15,910
inquired a slow voice behind us.

813
00:48:15,910 --> 00:48:19,853
I jumped round, and there
was the Virginian.

814
00:48:19,853 --> 00:48:21,184
“Male parent!”

815
00:48:21,184 --> 00:48:22,944
scoffed the prompt Scipio.

816
00:48:22,944 --> 00:48:24,744
“Ain’t you heard about them yet?”

817
00:48:24,744 --> 00:48:25,425
“Them?

818
00:48:25,425 --> 00:48:27,027
Was there two?”

819
00:48:27,027 --> 00:48:28,133
“Two?

820
00:48:28,133 --> 00:48:32,055
The blamed thing was sired by a
whole doggone Dutch syndicate.”

821
00:48:32,055 --> 00:48:35,037
“Why, the piebald son of a gun!”

822
00:48:35,037 --> 00:48:36,759
responded the Virginian, sweetly.

823
00:48:36,759 --> 00:48:40,172
“I got them steers through all right,”
he added to me.

824
00:48:40,172 --> 00:48:43,259
“Sorry to see yu’ get so out o’
breath afteh the train.

825
00:48:43,259 --> 00:48:45,170
Is your valise sufferin’ any?”

826
00:48:45,170 --> 00:48:45,994
“Who’s he?”

827
00:48:45,994 --> 00:48:49,033
inquired Scipio, curiously, turning to me.

828
00:48:49,033 --> 00:48:53,645
The Southerner sat with a newspaper on
the rear platform of a caboose.

829
00:48:53,645 --> 00:48:57,674
The caboose stood hitched behind a mile
or so of freight train,

830
00:48:57,674 --> 00:48:59,666
and the train was headed west.

831
00:48:59,666 --> 00:49:04,239
So here was the deputy foreman,
his steers delivered in Chicago,

832
00:49:04,239 --> 00:49:10,091
his men (I could hear them) safe in the
caboose, his paper in his lap,

833
00:49:10,091 --> 00:49:15,364
and his legs dangling at
ease over the railing.

834
00:49:15,364 --> 00:49:22,066
He wore the look of a man for whom
things are going smooth.

835
00:49:22,066 --> 00:49:26,172
And for me the way to Billings
was smooth now, also.

836
00:49:26,172 --> 00:49:27,257
“Who’s he?”

837
00:49:27,257 --> 00:49:29,084
Scipio repeated.

838
00:49:29,084 --> 00:49:36,106
But from inside the caboose loud laughter
and noise broke on us.

839
00:49:36,106 --> 00:49:38,677
Someone was reciting “And it’s
my night to howl.”

840
00:49:38,677 --> 00:49:44,895
“We’ll all howl when we get to Rawhide,”
said some other one; and they howled

841
00:49:44,895 --> 00:49:46,135
now.

842
00:49:46,135 --> 00:49:50,710
“These hyeh steam cyars,”
said the Virginian to Scipio,

843
00:49:50,710 --> 00:49:54,320
“make a man’s language mighty nigh as
speedy as his travel.”

844
00:49:54,320 --> 00:49:59,262
Of Shorty he took no notice whatever⁠—no
more than of the manifestations

845
00:49:59,262 --> 00:50:00,684
in the caboose.

846
00:50:00,684 --> 00:50:04,601
“So yu’ heard me speakin’ to
the express,” said Scipio.

847
00:50:04,601 --> 00:50:10,812
“Well, I guess, sometimes I⁠—See here,”
he exclaimed, for the Virginian was

848
00:50:10,812 --> 00:50:14,227
gravely considering him,
“I may have talked some,

849
00:50:14,227 --> 00:50:16,110
but I walked a whole lot.

850
00:50:16,110 --> 00:50:19,220
You didn’t catch me squandering no speed.

851
00:50:19,220 --> 00:50:20,560
Soon as⁠—”

852
00:50:20,560 --> 00:50:24,776
“I noticed,” said the Virginian,
“thinkin’ came quicker

853
00:50:24,776 --> 00:50:26,391
to yu’ than runnin’.”

854
00:50:26,391 --> 00:50:30,139
I was glad I was not Shorty,
to have my measure taken merely by my

855
00:50:30,139 --> 00:50:31,482
way of missing a train.

856
00:50:31,482 --> 00:50:35,401
And of course I was sorry that I
had kicked my valise.

857
00:50:35,401 --> 00:50:38,113
“Oh, I could tell yu’d been enjoyin’ us!”

858
00:50:38,113 --> 00:50:39,008
said Scipio.

859
00:50:39,008 --> 00:50:42,907
“Observin’ somebody else’s scrape always
kind o’ rests me too.

860
00:50:42,907 --> 00:50:45,254
Maybe you’re a philosopher,
but maybe there’s a pair of us

861
00:50:45,254 --> -1:59:59,000
drawd in this deal.

862
-1:59:59,000 --> 00:00:02,000
”

863
00:50:46,574 --> 00:50:50,654
Approval now grew plain upon the
face of the Virginian.

864
00:50:50,654 --> 00:50:54,635
“By your laigs,” said he,
“you are used to the saddle.”

865
00:50:54,635 --> 00:50:57,126
“I’d be called used to it, I expect.”

866
00:50:57,126 --> 00:51:02,707
“By your hands,” said the Southerner,
again, “you ain’t roped

867
00:51:02,707 --> 00:51:04,530
many steers lately.

868
00:51:04,530 --> 00:51:06,940
Been cookin’ or something?”

869
00:51:06,940 --> 00:51:10,230
“Say,” retorted Scipio,
“tell my future some now.

870
00:51:10,230 --> 00:51:12,710
Draw a conclusion from my mouth.”

871
00:51:12,710 --> 00:51:16,000
“I’m right distressed,”
answered the gentle Southerner,

872
00:51:16,000 --> 00:51:18,721
“we’ve not a drop in the outfit.”

873
00:51:18,721 --> 00:51:21,785
“Oh, drink with me uptown!”

874
00:51:21,785 --> 00:51:22,735
cried Scipio.

875
00:51:22,735 --> 00:51:24,142
“I’m pleased to death with yu’.”

876
00:51:24,142 --> 00:51:27,736
The Virginian glanced where the saloons
stood just behind the station,

877
00:51:27,736 --> 00:51:28,585
and shook his head.

878
00:51:28,585 --> 00:51:31,595
“Why, it ain’t a bit far
to whiskey from here!”

879
00:51:31,595 --> 00:51:33,877
urged the other, plaintively.

880
00:51:33,877 --> 00:51:36,470
“Step down, now.

881
00:51:36,470 --> 00:51:38,801
Scipio le Moyne’s my name.

882
00:51:38,801 --> 00:51:42,855
Yes, you’re lookin’ for my brass earrings.

883
00:51:42,855 --> 00:51:46,391
But there ain’t no earrings on me.

884
00:51:46,391 --> 00:51:49,604
I’ve been white for a hundred years.

885
00:51:49,604 --> 00:51:50,740
Step down.

886
00:51:50,740 --> -1:59:59,000
I’ve a forty-dollar thirst.

887
-1:59:59,000 --> 00:00:02,000
”

888
00:51:52,259 --> 00:51:55,237
“You’re certainly white,”
began the Virginian.

889
00:51:55,237 --> 00:51:55,792
“But⁠—”

890
00:51:55,792 --> 00:51:57,560
Here the caboose resumed:⁠—

891
00:51:57,560 --> 00:52:01,222
“I’m wild, and woolly,
and full of peas;I’m hard to curry above

892
00:52:01,222 --> 00:52:10,235
the knees;I’m a she-wolf from Bitter
Creek, andIt’s my night to ho‑o‑wl⁠—”

893
00:52:10,235 --> 00:52:15,331
And as they howled and stamped,
the wheels of the caboose began to turn

894
00:52:15,331 --> 00:52:17,325
gently and to murmur.

895
00:52:17,325 --> 00:52:19,296
The Virginian rose suddenly.

896
00:52:19,296 --> 00:52:24,385
“Will yu’ save that thirst and take
a forty-dollar job?”

897
00:52:24,385 --> 00:52:27,345
“Missin’ trains, profanity, or what?”

898
00:52:27,345 --> 00:52:28,295
said Scipio.

899
00:52:28,295 --> 00:52:30,335
“I’ll tell yu’ soon as I’m sure.”

900
00:52:30,335 --> 00:52:32,775
At this Scipio looked
hard at the Virginian.

901
00:52:32,775 --> 00:52:36,000
“Why, you’re talkin’ business!”

902
00:52:36,000 --> 00:52:40,508
said he, and leaped on the caboose,
where I was already.

903
00:52:40,508 --> 00:52:44,917
“I was thinkin’ of Rawhide,”
he added, “but I ain’t any more.”

904
00:52:44,917 --> 00:52:46,922
“Well, good luck!”

905
00:52:46,922 --> 00:52:49,723
said Shorty, on the track behind us.

906
00:52:49,723 --> 00:52:51,018
“Oh, say!”

907
00:52:51,018 --> 00:52:55,750
said Scipio, “he wanted to go on that
train, just like me.”

908
00:52:55,750 --> 00:52:58,290
“Get on,” called the Virginian.

909
00:52:58,290 --> 00:53:01,640
“But as to getting a job,
he ain’t just like you.”

910
00:53:01,640 --> 00:53:05,850
So Shorty came, like a lost dog when
you whistle to him.

911
00:53:05,850 --> 00:53:08,852
Our wheels clucked over
the mainline switch.

912
00:53:08,852 --> 00:53:12,984
A train-hand threw it shut after us,
jumped aboard, and returned

913
00:53:12,984 --> 00:53:14,815
forward over the roofs.

914
00:53:14,815 --> 00:53:19,196
Inside the caboose they had reached the
third howling of the she-wolf.

915
00:53:19,196 --> 00:53:20,214
“Friends of yourn?”

916
00:53:20,214 --> 00:53:21,255
said Scipio.

917
00:53:21,255 --> 00:53:24,403
“My outfit,” drawled the Virginian.

918
00:53:24,403 --> 00:53:26,190
“Do yu’ always travel outside?”

919
00:53:26,190 --> 00:53:27,540
inquired Scipio.

920
00:53:27,540 --> 00:53:30,870
“It’s lonesome in there,”
returned the deputy foreman.

921
00:53:30,870 --> 00:53:34,444
And here one of them came
out, slamming the door.

922
00:53:34,444 --> 00:53:35,114
“Hell!”

923
00:53:35,114 --> 00:53:37,766
he said, at sight of the distant town.

924
00:53:37,766 --> 00:53:42,033
Then, truculently, to the Virginian,
“I told you I was going to

925
00:53:42,033 --> 00:53:43,623
get a bottle here.”

926
00:53:43,623 --> 00:53:46,692
“Have your bottle, then,”
said the deputy foreman,

927
00:53:46,692 --> 00:53:48,408
and kicked him off into Dakota.

928
00:53:48,408 --> 00:53:51,562
(It was not North Dakota yet;
they had not divided it.)

929
00:53:51,562 --> 00:53:57,141
The Virginian had aimed his pistol at
about the same time with his boot.

930
00:53:57,141 --> 00:54:03,009
Therefore the man sat in Dakota quietly,
watching us go away into Montana,

931
00:54:03,009 --> 00:54:05,469
and offering no objections.

932
00:54:05,469 --> 00:54:11,241
Just before he became too small to make
out, we saw him rise and remove himself

933
00:54:11,241 --> 00:54:13,390
back toward the saloons.

934
00:54:13,390 --> 00:54:14,390
CHAPTER XV

935
00:54:14,390 --> 00:54:17,379
The Game and the Nation⁠—Act Second

936
00:54:17,379 --> 00:54:22,964
“That is the only step I have had to take
this whole trip,” said the Virginian.

937
00:54:22,964 --> 00:54:25,195
He holstered his pistol with a jerk.

938
00:54:25,195 --> 00:54:28,179
“I have been fearing he would
force it on me.”

939
00:54:28,179 --> 00:54:31,796
And he looked at empty,
receding Dakota with disgust.

940
00:54:31,796 --> 00:54:34,175
“So nyeh back home!”

941
00:54:34,175 --> 00:54:35,391
he muttered.

942
00:54:35,391 --> 00:54:37,001
“Known your friend long?”

943
00:54:37,001 --> 00:54:38,515
whispered Scipio to me.

944
00:54:38,515 --> 00:54:40,111
“Fairly,” I answered.

945
00:54:40,111 --> 00:54:45,138
Scipio’s bleached eyes brightened with
admiration as he considered

946
00:54:45,138 --> 00:54:46,303
the Southerner’s back.

947
00:54:46,303 --> 00:54:51,068
“Well,” he stated judicially,
“start awful early when yu’ go to fool

948
00:54:51,068 --> 00:54:54,039
with him, or he’ll make
you feel unpunctual.”

949
00:54:54,039 --> 00:54:58,901
“I expaict I’ve had them almost all of
three thousand miles,”

950
00:54:58,901 --> 00:55:04,114
said the Virginian, tilting his head
toward the noise in the caboose.

951
00:55:04,114 --> 00:55:07,701
“And I’ve strove to deliver them back
as I received them.

952
00:55:07,701 --> 00:55:08,895
The whole lot.

953
00:55:08,895 --> 00:55:10,625
And I would have.

954
00:55:10,625 --> 00:55:12,584
But he has spoiled my hopes.”

955
00:55:12,584 --> 00:55:15,676
The deputy foreman looked again at Dakota.

956
00:55:15,676 --> 00:55:17,637
“It’s a disappointment,” he added.

957
00:55:17,637 --> 00:55:19,575
“You may know what I mean.”

958
00:55:19,575 --> 00:55:22,989
I had known a little,
but not to the very deep,

959
00:55:22,989 --> 00:55:28,882
of the man’s pride and
purpose in this trust.

960
00:55:28,882 --> 00:55:30,961
Scipio gave him sympathy.

961
00:55:30,961 --> 00:55:33,932
“There must be quite a balance of ’em
left with yu’ yet,” said

962
00:55:33,932 --> 00:55:35,092
Scipio, cheeringly.

963
00:55:35,092 --> 00:55:39,524
“I had the boys plumb contented,”
pursued the deputy foreman,

964
00:55:39,524 --> 00:55:42,016
hurt into open talk of himself.

965
00:55:42,016 --> 00:55:48,044
“Away along as far as Saynt Paul I had
them reconciled to my authority.

966
00:55:48,044 --> 00:55:50,176
Then this news about gold
had to strike us.”

967
00:55:50,176 --> 00:55:54,738
“And they’re a-dreamin’ nuggets and
Parisian bowleyvards,” suggested Scipio.

968
00:55:54,738 --> 00:55:58,232
The Virginian smiled gratefully at him.

969
00:55:58,232 --> 00:56:04,967
“Fortune is shinin’ bright and blindin’
to their delicate young eyes,”

970
00:56:04,967 --> 00:56:07,413
he said, regaining his usual self.

971
00:56:07,413 --> 00:56:10,407
We all listened a moment
to the rejoicings within.

972
00:56:10,407 --> 00:56:12,218
“Energetic, ain’t they?”

973
00:56:12,218 --> 00:56:13,304
said the Southerner.

974
00:56:13,304 --> 00:56:18,332
“But none of ’em was whelped savage
enough to sing himself bloodthirsty.

975
00:56:18,332 --> 00:56:21,192
And though they’re strainin’ mighty
earnest not to be tame,

976
00:56:21,192 --> -1:59:59,000
they’re goin’ back to Sunk Creek with me
accordin’ to the Judge’s awders

977
-1:59:59,000 --> 00:00:02,000
.

978
00:56:24,951 --> 00:56:29,262
Never a calf of them will desert to
Rawhide, for all their dangerousness;

979
00:56:29,262 --> 00:56:32,302
nor I ain’t goin’ to have
any fuss over it.

980
00:56:32,302 --> 00:56:36,779
Only one is left now that don’t sing.

981
00:56:36,779 --> 00:56:39,495
Maybe I will have to make
some arrangements about him.

982
00:56:39,495 --> 00:56:44,042
The man I have parted with,”
he said, with another glance

983
00:56:44,042 --> 00:56:44,251
at

984
00:56:44,251 --> 00:56:44,934
Dakota

985
00:56:44,934 --> 00:56:49,262
, “was our cook, and I will ask yu’
to replace him, Colonel.”

986
00:56:49,262 --> 00:56:51,065
Scipio gaped wide.

987
00:56:51,065 --> 00:56:52,140
“Colonel!

988
00:56:52,140 --> 00:56:52,991
Say!”

989
00:56:52,991 --> 00:56:54,822
He stared at the Virginian.

990
00:56:54,822 --> 00:56:56,942
“Did I meet yu’ at the palace?”

991
00:56:56,942 --> 00:57:00,161
“Not exackly meet,” replied
the Southerner.

992
00:57:00,161 --> 00:57:03,792
“I was present one mawnin’ las’ month
when this gentleman awdehed

993
00:57:03,792 --> 00:57:05,314
frawgs’ laigs.”

994
00:57:05,314 --> 00:57:09,028
“Sakes and saints, but that
was a mean position!”

995
00:57:09,028 --> 00:57:10,657
burst out Scipio.

996
00:57:10,657 --> 00:57:13,530
“I had to tell all comers
anything all day.

997
00:57:13,530 --> 00:57:17,348
Stand up and jump language hot off
my brain at ’em.

998
00:57:17,348 --> 00:57:22,481
And the pay don’t near compensate for the
drain on the system.

999
00:57:22,481 --> 00:57:26,934
I don’t care how good a man is,
you let him keep a-tappin’ his presence

1000
00:57:26,934 --> 00:57:29,459
of mind right along,
without takin’ a layoff,

1001
00:57:29,459 --> 00:57:30,836
and you’ll have him sick.

1002
00:57:30,836 --> 00:57:31,654
Yes, sir.

1003
00:57:31,654 --> 00:57:33,296
You’ll hit his nerves.

1004
00:57:33,296 --> 00:57:38,674
So I told them they could hire some fresh
man, for I was goin’ back to punch

1005
00:57:38,674 --> 00:57:42,510
cattle or fight Indians,
or take a rest somehow,

1006
00:57:42,510 --> 00:57:47,221
for I didn’t propose to get jaded,
and me only twenty-five years old.

1007
00:57:47,221 --> 00:57:50,635
There ain’t no regular Colonel Cyrus
Jones any more, yu’ know.

1008
00:57:50,635 --> 00:57:55,559
He met a Cheyenne telegraph pole in
seventy-four, and was buried.

1009
00:57:55,559 --> 00:57:59,565
But his palace was doin’ big business,
and he had been a kind of attraction,

1010
00:57:59,565 --> 00:58:03,764
and so they always keep a live bear
outside, and some poor fello’, fixed up

1011
00:58:03,764 --> 00:58:07,297
like the Colonel used to be, inside.

1012
00:58:07,297 --> 00:58:09,835
And it’s a turruble mean position.

1013
00:58:09,835 --> 00:58:11,860
Course I’ll cook for yu’.

1014
00:58:11,860 --> 00:58:14,342
Yu’ve a dandy memory for faces!”

1015
00:58:14,342 --> 00:58:19,148
“I wasn’t right convinced till I kicked
him off and you gave that shut to your

1016
00:58:19,148 --> 00:58:20,550
eyes again,” said the Virginian.

1017
00:58:20,550 --> 00:58:23,591
Once more the door opened.

1018
00:58:23,591 --> 00:58:28,685
A man with slim black eyebrows,
slim black mustache,

1019
00:58:28,685 --> 00:58:33,595
and a black shirt tied with a white
handkerchief was looking steadily from

1020
00:58:33,595 --> 00:58:35,817
one to the other of us.

1021
00:58:35,817 --> 00:58:37,040
“Good day!”

1022
00:58:37,040 --> 00:58:39,808
he remarked generally and without
enthusiasm; and to the

1023
00:58:39,808 --> 00:58:42,602
Virginian, “Where’s Schoffner?”

1024
00:58:42,602 --> 00:58:45,436
“I expaict he’ll have got his
bottle by now, Trampas.”

1025
00:58:45,436 --> 00:58:47,851
Trampas looked from one to the
other of us again.

1026
00:58:47,851 --> 00:58:50,376
“Didn’t he say he was coming back?”

1027
00:58:50,376 --> 00:58:53,552
“He reminded me he was going for a
bottle, and afteh that he didn’t wait

1028
00:58:53,552 --> 00:58:54,552
to say a thing.”

1029
00:58:54,552 --> 00:58:57,558
Trampas looked at the platform and the
railing and the steps.

1030
00:58:57,558 --> 00:59:00,806
“He told me he was coming
back,” he insisted.

1031
00:59:00,806 --> 00:59:06,214
“I don’t reckon he has come,
not without he clumb up ahaid somewhere.

1032
00:59:06,214 --> 00:59:10,966
An’ I mus’ say, when he got off he didn’t
look like a man does when he has

1033
00:59:10,966 --> -1:59:59,000
the intention o’ returnin’.

1034
-1:59:59,000 --> 00:00:02,000
”

1035
00:59:12,534 --> 00:59:16,587
At this Scipio coughed,
and pared his nails attentively.

1036
00:59:16,587 --> 00:59:19,671
We had already been avoiding
each other’s eye.

1037
00:59:19,671 --> 00:59:21,214
Shorty did not count.

1038
00:59:21,214 --> 00:59:25,527
Since he got aboard, his meek seat had
been the bottom step.

1039
00:59:25,527 --> 00:59:29,620
The thoughts of Trampas seemed
to be in difficulty.

1040
00:59:29,620 --> 00:59:32,261
“How long’s this train been started?”

1041
00:59:32,261 --> 00:59:33,087
he demanded.

1042
00:59:33,087 --> 00:59:34,694
“This hyeh train?”

1043
00:59:34,694 --> 00:59:37,007
The Virginian consulted his watch.

1044
00:59:37,007 --> 00:59:41,132
“Why, it’s been fanning it a right smart
little while,” said he,

1045
00:59:41,132 --> 00:59:44,412
laying no stress upon
his indolent syllables.

1046
00:59:44,412 --> 00:59:44,953
“Huh!”

1047
00:59:44,953 --> 00:59:46,563
went Trampas.

1048
00:59:46,563 --> 00:59:51,132
He gave the rest of us
a final unlovely scrutiny.

1049
00:59:51,132 --> 00:59:54,860
“It seems to have become a
passenger train,” he said.

1050
00:59:54,860 --> 00:59:58,497
And he returned abruptly
inside the caboose.

1051
00:59:58,497 --> 01:00:00,530
“Is he the member who don’t sing?”

1052
01:00:00,530 --> 01:00:01,609
asked Scipio.

1053
01:00:01,609 --> 01:00:04,519
“That’s the specimen,”
replied the Southerner.

1054
01:00:04,519 --> 01:00:08,140
“He don’t seem musical in
the face,” said Scipio.

1055
01:00:08,140 --> 01:00:08,834
“Pshaw!”

1056
01:00:08,834 --> 01:00:10,553
returned the Virginian.

1057
01:00:10,553 --> 01:00:15,194
“Why, you surely ain’t the man to mind
ugly mugs when they’re hollow!”

1058
01:00:15,194 --> 01:00:18,110
The noise inside had dropped
quickly to stillness.

1059
01:00:18,110 --> 01:00:20,390
You could scarcely catch
the sound of talk.

1060
01:00:20,390 --> 01:00:26,198
Our caboose was clicking comfortably
westward, rail after rail,

1061
01:00:26,198 --> 01:00:30,734
mile upon mile, while night was
beginning to rise from earth

1062
01:00:30,734 --> 01:00:32,439
into the clouded sky.

1063
01:00:32,439 --> 01:00:36,525
“I wonder if they have sent a search
party forward to hunt Schoffner?”

1064
01:00:36,525 --> 01:00:37,706
said the Virginian.

1065
01:00:37,706 --> 01:00:39,931
“I think I’ll maybe join their meeting.”

1066
01:00:39,931 --> 01:00:41,439
He opened the door upon them.

1067
01:00:41,439 --> 01:00:44,392
“Kind o’ dark hyeh, ain’t it?”

1068
01:00:44,392 --> 01:00:45,574
said he.

1069
01:00:45,574 --> 01:00:48,613
And lighting the lantern, he shut us out.

1070
01:00:48,613 --> 01:00:51,318
“What do yu’ think?”

1071
01:00:51,318 --> 01:00:53,579
said Scipio to me.

1072
01:00:53,579 --> 01:00:56,420
“Will he take them to Sunk Creek?”

1073
01:00:56,420 --> 01:00:59,360
“He evidently thinks he will,” said I.

1074
01:00:59,360 --> 01:01:03,680
“He says he will, and he has the
courage of his convictions.”

1075
01:01:03,680 --> 01:01:05,776
“That ain’t near enough courage to have!”

1076
01:01:05,776 --> 01:01:07,344
Scipio exclaimed.

1077
01:01:07,344 --> 01:01:11,960
“There’s times in life when a man has got
to have courage withoutconvictions⁠—

1078
01:01:11,960 --> 01:01:14,519
without them⁠—or he is no good.

1079
01:01:14,519 --> 01:01:19,754
Now your friend is that deep constitooted
that you don’t know and I don’t know

1080
01:01:19,754 --> 01:01:21,987
what he’s thinkin’ about all this.”

1081
01:01:21,987 --> 01:01:25,867
“If there’s to be any gunplay,”
put in the excellent Shorty,

1082
01:01:25,867 --> 01:01:27,164
“I’ll stand in with him.”

1083
01:01:27,164 --> 01:01:30,079
“Ah, go to bed with your gunplay!”

1084
01:01:30,079 --> 01:01:33,656
retorted Scipio, entirely good-humored.

1085
01:01:33,656 --> 01:01:38,340
“Is the Judge paying for a carload of
dead punchers to gather his beef for

1086
01:01:38,340 --> 01:01:38,785
him?

1087
01:01:38,785 --> 01:01:42,769
And this ain’t a proposition worth a
man’s gettin’ hurt for himself, anyway.”

1088
01:01:42,769 --> 01:01:45,492
“That’s so,” Shorty assented.

1089
01:01:45,492 --> 01:01:51,090
“No,” speculated Scipio,
as the night drew deeper round us and

1090
01:01:51,090 --> 01:01:54,340
the caboose click-clucked and click-
clucked over the rail joints;

1091
01:01:54,340 --> 01:01:56,651
“he’s waitin’ for somebody else
to open this pot.

1092
01:01:56,651 --> 01:02:00,340
I’ll bet he don’t know but one thing now,
and that’s that nobody else shall know

1093
01:02:00,340 --> 01:02:01,875
he don’t know anything.”

1094
01:02:01,875 --> 01:02:03,932
Scipio had delivered himself.

1095
01:02:03,932 --> 01:02:07,272
He lighted a cigarette,
and no more wisdom came from him.

1096
01:02:07,272 --> 01:02:10,125
The night was established.

1097
01:02:10,125 --> 01:02:12,833
The rolling badlands sank away in it.

1098
01:02:12,833 --> 01:02:18,268
A train-hand had arrived over the roof,
and hanging the red lights out behind,

1099
01:02:18,268 --> 01:02:23,497
left us again without remark
or symptom of curiosity.

1100
01:02:23,497 --> 01:02:27,705
The train-hands seemed interested in
their own society and lived

1101
01:02:27,705 --> 01:02:30,358
in their own caboose.

1102
01:02:30,358 --> 01:02:35,758
A chill wind with wet in it came blowing
from the invisible draws,

1103
01:02:35,758 --> -1:59:59,000
and brought the feel
of the distant mountains

1104
-1:59:59,000 --> 00:00:02,000
.

1105
01:02:39,936 --> 01:02:41,387
“That’s Montana!”

1106
01:02:41,387 --> 01:02:44,031
said Scipio, snuffing.

1107
01:02:44,031 --> 01:02:46,591
“I am glad to have it
inside my lungs again.”

1108
01:02:46,591 --> 01:02:48,696
“Ain’t yu’ getting cool out there?”

1109
01:02:48,696 --> 01:02:50,465
said the Virginian’s voice.

1110
01:02:50,465 --> 01:02:52,017
“Plenty room inside.”

1111
01:02:52,017 --> 01:02:56,892
Perhaps he had expected us to follow him;
or perhaps he had meant us to delay long

1112
01:02:56,892 --> 01:02:59,993
enough not to seem like a reinforcement.

1113
01:02:59,993 --> 01:03:05,394
“These gentlemen missed the express at
Medora,” he observed to his men, simply.

1114
01:03:05,394 --> 01:03:09,978
What they took us for upon our entrance I
cannot say, or what they believed.

1115
01:03:09,978 --> 01:03:16,012
The atmosphere of the caboose was charged
with voiceless currents of thought.

1116
01:03:16,012 --> 01:03:20,633
By way of a friendly beginning to the
three hundred miles of caboose we were

1117
01:03:20,633 --> 01:03:24,273
now to share so intimately,
I recalled myself to them.

1118
01:03:24,273 --> 01:03:27,633
I trusted no more of the Christian
Endeavor had delayed them.

1119
01:03:27,633 --> 01:03:31,102
“I am so lucky to have caught
you again,” I finished.

1120
01:03:31,102 --> 01:03:34,527
“I was afraid my last chance of reaching
the Judge’s had gone.”

1121
01:03:34,527 --> 01:03:38,353
Thus I said a number of things designed
to be agreeable, but they met my small

1122
01:03:38,353 --> 01:03:40,375
talk with the smallest talk you can
have.

1123
01:03:40,375 --> 01:03:46,951
“Yes,” for instance, and “Pretty well,
I guess,” and grave strikings of matches

1124
01:03:46,951 --> -1:59:59,000
and thoughtful looks at the floor

1125
-1:59:59,000 --> 00:00:02,000
.

1126
01:03:48,784 --> 01:03:52,704
I suppose we had made twenty miles to the
imperturbable clicking of the caboose

1127
01:03:52,704 --> 01:03:56,067
when one at length asked his neighbor
had he ever seen New York.

1128
01:03:56,067 --> 01:03:58,265
“No,” said the other.

1129
01:03:58,265 --> -1:59:59,000
“Flooded with dudes, ain’t it?

1130
-1:59:59,000 --> 00:00:02,000
”

1131
01:04:01,269 --> 01:04:04,045
“Swimmin’,” said the first.

1132
01:04:04,045 --> 01:04:06,767
“Leakin’, too,” said a third.

1133
01:04:06,767 --> 01:04:08,721
“Well, my gracious!”

1134
01:04:08,721 --> 01:04:12,105
said a fourth, and beat his
knee in private delight.

1135
01:04:12,105 --> 01:04:14,120
None of them ever looked at me.

1136
01:04:14,120 --> 01:04:18,831
For some reason I felt
exceedingly ill at ease.

1137
01:04:18,831 --> 01:04:22,023
“Good clothes in New York,”
said the third.

1138
01:04:22,023 --> 01:04:24,375
“Rich food,” said the first.

1139
01:04:24,375 --> 01:04:27,422
“Fresh eggs, too,” said the third.

1140
01:04:27,422 --> 01:04:29,649
“Well, my gracious!”

1141
01:04:29,649 --> 01:04:31,733
said the fourth, beating his knee.

1142
01:04:31,733 --> 01:04:36,249
“Why, yes,” observed the Virginian,
unexpectedly; “they tell me that aiggs

1143
01:04:36,249 --> 01:04:40,631
there ain’t liable to be so rotten as
yu’ll strike ’em in this country.”

1144
01:04:40,631 --> 01:04:44,184
None of them had a reply for this,
and New York was abandoned.

1145
01:04:44,184 --> 01:04:46,112
For some reason I felt much better.

1146
01:04:46,112 --> 01:04:50,231
It was a new line they adopted next,
led off by Trampas.

1147
01:04:50,231 --> 01:04:51,571
“Going to the excitement?”

1148
01:04:51,571 --> 01:04:54,299
he inquired, selecting Shorty.

1149
01:04:54,299 --> 01:04:55,331
“Excitement?”

1150
01:04:55,331 --> 01:04:56,736
said Shorty, looking up.

1151
01:04:56,736 --> 01:04:58,842
“Going to Rawhide?”

1152
01:04:58,842 --> 01:05:00,310
Trampas repeated.

1153
01:05:00,310 --> 01:05:01,974
And all watched Shorty.

1154
01:05:01,974 --> 01:05:05,982
“Why, I’m all adrift missin’
that express,” said Shorty.

1155
01:05:05,982 --> 01:05:11,180
“Maybe I can give you
employment,” suggested the Virginian.

1156
01:05:11,180 --> 01:05:13,300
“I am taking an outfit across the basin.”

1157
01:05:13,300 --> 01:05:16,374
“You’ll find most folks going to Rawhide,
if you’re looking for company,”

1158
01:05:16,374 --> 01:05:19,054
pursued Trampas, fishing for a recruit.

1159
01:05:19,054 --> 01:05:20,844
“How about Rawhide, anyway?”

1160
01:05:20,844 --> 01:05:24,589
said Scipio, skillfully
deflecting this missionary work.

1161
01:05:24,589 --> 01:05:26,636
“Are they taking much mineral out?

1162
01:05:26,636 --> 01:05:29,309
Have yu’ seen any of the rock?”

1163
01:05:29,309 --> 01:05:30,300
“Rock?”

1164
01:05:30,300 --> 01:05:34,075
broke in the enthusiast who
had beaten his knee.

1165
01:05:34,075 --> 01:05:34,964
“There!”

1166
01:05:34,964 --> 01:05:36,828
And he brought some from his pocket.

1167
01:05:36,828 --> 01:05:40,852
“You’re always showing your rock,”
said Trampas, sulkily;

1168
01:05:40,852 --> 01:05:45,449
for Scipio now held the conversation,
and Shorty returned safely to his

1169
01:05:45,449 --> 01:05:46,569
dozing.

1170
01:05:46,569 --> 01:05:46,624
“H’m!”

1171
01:05:46,624 --> 01:05:48,064
went Scipio at the rock.

1172
01:05:48,064 --> 01:05:52,602
He turned it back and forth in his hand,
looking it over; he chucked and caught

1173
01:05:52,602 --> 01:05:55,760
it slightingly in the air,
and handed it back.

1174
01:05:55,760 --> 01:05:56,991
“Porphyry, I see.”

1175
01:05:56,991 --> 01:05:58,753
That was his only word about it.

1176
01:05:58,753 --> 01:06:00,596
He said it cheerily.

1177
01:06:00,596 --> 01:06:03,834
He left no room for discussion.

1178
01:06:03,834 --> 01:06:06,386
You could not damn a thing worse.

1179
01:06:06,386 --> 01:06:08,834
“Ever been in Santa Rita?”

1180
01:06:08,834 --> 01:06:13,365
pursued Scipio, while the enthusiast
slowly pushed his rock

1181
01:06:13,365 --> 01:06:14,464
back into his pocket.

1182
01:06:14,464 --> 01:06:16,381
“That’s down in New Mexico.

1183
01:06:16,381 --> 01:06:18,529
Ever been to Globe, Arizona?”

1184
01:06:18,529 --> 01:06:21,406
And Scipio talked away about the
mines he had known.

1185
01:06:21,406 --> 01:06:24,523
There was no getting at Shorty
any more that evening.

1186
01:06:24,523 --> 01:06:29,322
Trampas was foiled of his fish,
or of learning how the fish’s heart lay.

1187
01:06:29,322 --> 01:06:32,834
And by morning Shorty had been carefully
instructed to change his mind

1188
01:06:32,834 --> 01:06:34,433
about once an hour.

1189
01:06:34,433 --> 01:06:39,255
This is apt to discourage all
but very superior missionaries.

1190
01:06:39,255 --> 01:06:41,815
And I too escaped for the
rest of this night.

1191
01:06:41,815 --> 01:06:47,881
At Glendive we had a dim supper,
and I bought some blankets;

1192
01:06:47,881 --> 01:06:52,188
and after that it was late,
and sleep occupied the

1193
01:06:52,188 --> 01:06:53,634
attention of us all.

1194
01:06:53,634 --> 01:06:59,438
We lay along the shelves of the caboose,
a peaceful sight I should think,

1195
01:06:59,438 --> 01:07:02,404
in that smoothly trundling cradle.

1196
01:07:02,404 --> 01:07:07,275
I slept almost immediately,
so tired that not even our stops or

1197
01:07:07,275 --> 01:07:12,293
anything else waked me,
save once, when the air I was breathing

1198
01:07:12,293 --> 01:07:14,621
grew suddenly pure, and I roused.

1199
01:07:14,621 --> 01:07:19,255
Sitting in the door was the lonely
figure of the Virginian.

1200
01:07:19,255 --> 01:07:23,317
He leaned in silent contemplation of the
occasional moon, and beneath it

1201
01:07:23,317 --> 01:07:26,062
the Yellowstone’s swift ripples.

1202
01:07:26,062 --> 01:07:31,480
On the caboose shelves the others slept
sound and still, each stretched or

1203
01:07:31,480 --> 01:07:34,160
coiled as he had first put himself.

1204
01:07:34,160 --> 01:07:39,481
They were not untrustworthy to look at,
it seemed to me⁠—except Trampas.

1205
01:07:39,481 --> 01:07:43,932
You would have said the rest of that
young humanity was average rough male

1206
01:07:43,932 --> 01:07:48,212
blood, merely needing to be told the
proper things at the right time;

1207
01:07:48,212 --> 01:07:53,772
and one big bunchy stocking of the
enthusiast stuck out of his blanket,

1208
01:07:53,772 --> 01:07:57,011
solemn and innocent, and I laughed at
it.

1209
01:07:57,011 --> 01:08:01,694
There was a light sound by the door,
and I found the Virginian’s eye on me.

1210
01:08:01,694 --> 01:08:06,382
Finding who it was, he nodded and
motioned with his hand to go to sleep.

1211
01:08:06,382 --> 01:08:10,029
And this I did with him in my sight,
still leaning in the open door,

1212
01:08:10,029 --> 01:08:12,932
through which came the interrupted moon
and the swimming reaches

1213
01:08:12,932 --> 01:08:13,892
of the Yellowstone.

1214
01:08:13,892 --> 01:08:14,732
