1253
01:10:28,145 --> 01:10:30,421
trundle by the banks of the Yellowstone.

1254
01:10:30,421 --> 01:10:35,136
The mutineers sat for a
while digesting in idleness.

1255
01:10:35,136 --> 01:10:36,600
“What’s your scar?”

1256
01:10:36,600 --> 01:10:40,245
inquired one at length inspecting
casually the neck of his neighbor.

1257
01:10:40,245 --> 01:10:42,131
“Foolishness,” the other answered.

1258
01:10:42,131 --> 01:10:42,856
“Yourn?”

1259
01:10:42,856 --> 01:10:44,357
“Mine.”

1260
01:10:44,357 --> 01:10:48,901
“Well, I don’t know but I prefer to have
myself to thank for a

1261
01:10:48,901 --> 01:10:50,451
thing,” said the first.

1262
01:10:50,451 --> 01:10:53,731
“I was displaying myself,”
continued the second.

1263
01:10:53,731 --> 01:10:56,123
“One day last summer it was.

1264
01:10:56,123 --> 01:10:59,981
We come on a big snake
by Torrey Creek corral.

1265
01:10:59,981 --> 01:11:04,135
The boys got betting pretty lively that I
dassent make my word good as to dealing

1266
01:11:04,135 --> 01:11:09,977
with him, so I loped my cayuse full tilt
by Mr. Snake, and swung down and catched

1267
01:11:09,977 --> 01:11:13,947
him up by the tail from the ground,
and cracked him same as a whip,

1268
01:11:13,947 --> 01:11:15,731
and snapped his head off.

1269
01:11:15,731 --> 01:11:16,919
You’ve saw it done?”

1270
01:11:16,919 --> 01:11:18,369
he said to the audience.

1271
01:11:18,369 --> 01:11:20,984
The audience nodded wearily.

1272
01:11:20,984 --> 01:11:26,240
“But the loose head flew agin me,
and the fangs caught.

1273
01:11:26,240 --> -1:59:59,000
I was pretty sick for a while.

1274
-1:59:59,000 --> 00:00:02,000
”

1275
01:11:28,233 --> 01:11:31,083
“It don’t pay to be clumsy,”
said the first man.

1276
01:11:31,083 --> 01:11:36,774
“If you’d snapped the snake away from yu’
instead of toward yu’, its head would

1277
01:11:36,774 --> 01:11:40,650
have whirled off into the brush,
same as they do with me.”

1278
01:11:40,650 --> 01:11:44,516
“How like a knife-cut your scar looks!”

1279
01:11:44,516 --> 01:11:45,101
said I.

1280
01:11:45,101 --> 01:11:45,463
“Don’t it?”

1281
01:11:45,463 --> 01:11:47,399
said the snake-snapper.

1282
01:11:47,399 --> 01:11:49,769
“There’s many that gets fooled by it.”

1283
01:11:49,769 --> 01:11:54,019
“An antelope knows a snake is his enemy,”
said another to me.

1284
01:11:54,019 --> 01:11:57,263
“Ever seen a buck circling round
and round a rattler?”

1285
01:11:57,263 --> 01:12:01,340
“I have always wanted to see
that,” said I, heartily.

1286
01:12:01,340 --> 01:12:04,380
For this I knew to be a
respectable piece of truth.

1287
01:12:04,380 --> 01:12:06,651
“It’s worth seeing,” the man went on.

1288
01:12:06,651 --> 01:12:11,050
“After the buck gets close in,
he gives an almighty jump up in the air,

1289
01:12:11,050 --> 01:12:14,990
and down comes his four hoofs in a bunch
right on top of Mr. Snake.

1290
01:12:14,990 --> 01:12:16,691
Cuts him all to hash.

1291
01:12:16,691 --> -1:59:59,000
Now you tell me how the buck knows that.

1292
-1:59:59,000 --> 00:00:02,000
”

1293
01:12:18,702 --> 01:12:20,439
Of course I could not tell him.

1294
01:12:20,439 --> 01:12:25,145
And again we sat in silence for a while⁠—
friendlier silence, I thought.

1295
01:12:25,145 --> 01:12:29,566
“A skunk’ll kill yu’ worse than a snake
bite,” said another, presently.

1296
01:12:29,566 --> 01:12:34,331
“No, I don’t mean that way,” he added.

1297
01:12:34,331 --> 01:12:35,585
For I had smiled.

1298
01:12:35,585 --> 01:12:39,182
“There is a brown skunk down in Arkansaw.

1299
01:12:39,182 --> 01:12:41,498
Kind of prairie-dog brown.

1300
01:12:41,498 --> 01:12:44,518
Littler than our variety, he is.

1301
01:12:44,518 --> 01:12:49,914
And he is mad the whole year round,
same as a dog gets.

1302
01:12:49,914 --> 01:12:55,360
Only the dog has a spell and dies but
this here Arkansaw skunk is mad right

1303
01:12:55,360 --> 01:12:58,932
along, and it don’t seem to interfere
with his business in other respects.

1304
01:12:58,932 --> 01:13:03,103
Well, suppose you’re camping out,
and suppose it’s a hot night,

1305
01:13:03,103 --> 01:13:05,854
or you’re in a hurry,
and you’ve made camp late,

1306
01:13:05,854 --> 01:13:10,495
or anyway you haven’t got inside any
tent, but you have just bedded

1307
01:13:10,495 --> 01:13:11,600
down in the open.

1308
01:13:11,600 --> 01:13:15,568
Skunk comes travelling along and
walks on your blankets.

1309
01:13:15,568 --> 01:13:16,395
You’re warm.

1310
01:13:16,395 --> 01:13:18,783
He likes that, same as a cat does.

1311
01:13:18,783 --> 01:13:22,896
And he tramps with pleasure and comfort,
same as a cat.

1312
01:13:22,896 --> 01:13:24,779
And you move.

1313
01:13:24,779 --> 01:13:27,337
You get bit, that’s all.

1314
01:13:27,337 --> 01:13:31,047
And you die of hydrophobia.

1315
01:13:31,047 --> -1:59:59,000
Ask anybody.

1316
-1:59:59,000 --> 00:00:02,000
”

1317
01:13:33,498 --> 01:13:35,774
“Most extraordinary!”

1318
01:13:35,774 --> 01:13:37,253
said I.

1319
01:13:37,253 --> 01:13:48,704
“But did you ever see a
person die from this?”

1320
01:13:48,704 --> 01:13:51,757
“No, sir.

1321
01:13:51,757 --> 01:13:55,358
Never happened to.

1322
01:13:55,358 --> 01:13:57,518
My cousin at Bald Knob did.”

1323
01:13:57,518 --> 01:13:58,301
“Died?”

1324
01:13:58,301 --> 01:13:59,264
“No, sir.

1325
01:13:59,264 --> 01:14:00,472
Saw a man.”

1326
01:14:00,472 --> 01:14:03,388
“But how do you know they’re
not sick skunks?”

1327
01:14:03,388 --> 01:14:04,157
“No, sir!

1328
01:14:04,157 --> 01:14:05,409
They’re well skunks.

1329
01:14:05,409 --> 01:14:07,824
Well as anything.

1330
01:14:07,824 --> 01:14:11,639
You’ll not meet skunks in any state of
the Union more robust

1331
01:14:11,639 --> 01:14:13,580
than them in Arkansaw.

1332
01:14:13,580 --> 01:14:14,632
And thick.”

1333
01:14:14,632 --> 01:14:17,519
“That’s awful true,” sighed another.

1334
01:14:17,519 --> 01:14:22,156
“I have buried hundreds of dollars’ worth
of clothes in Arkansaw.”

1335
01:14:22,156 --> 01:14:24,758
“Why didn’t yu’ travel in a sponge bag?”

1336
01:14:24,758 --> 01:14:26,830
inquired Scipio.

1337
01:14:26,830 --> 01:14:28,683
And this brought a slight silence.

1338
01:14:28,683 --> 01:14:32,941
“Speakin’ of bites,” spoke up a
new man, “how’s that?”

1339
01:14:32,941 --> 01:14:34,078
He held up his thumb.

1340
01:14:34,078 --> 01:14:34,765
“My!”

1341
01:14:34,765 --> 01:14:35,908
breathed Scipio.

1342
01:14:35,908 --> 01:14:37,374
“Must have been a lion.”

1343
01:14:37,374 --> 01:14:39,115
The man wore a wounded look.

1344
01:14:39,115 --> 01:14:44,528
“I was huntin’ owl eggs for a botanist
from Boston,” he explained to me.

1345
01:14:44,528 --> 01:14:46,961
“Chiropodist, weren’t he?”

1346
01:14:46,961 --> 01:14:49,642
said Scipio.

1347
01:14:49,642 --> 01:14:51,203
“Or maybe a sonnabulator?”

1348
01:14:51,203 --> 01:14:56,719
“No, honest,” protested the man with the
thumb; so that I was sorry for him,

1349
01:14:56,719 --> 01:14:58,409
and begged him to go on.

1350
01:14:58,409 --> 01:15:00,787
“I’ll listen to you,” I assured him.

1351
01:15:00,787 --> 01:15:04,193
And I wondered why this politeness of
mine should throw one or two of

1352
01:15:04,193 --> 01:15:05,690
them into stifled mirth.

1353
01:15:05,690 --> 01:15:10,250
Scipio, on the other hand,
gave me a disgusted look and sat back

1354
01:15:10,250 --> 01:15:12,730
sullenly for a moment,
and then took himself out on the

1355
01:15:12,730 --> 01:15:15,162
platform, where the Virginian
was lounging.

1356
01:15:15,162 --> 01:15:19,845
“The young feller wore knee-pants and
ever so thick spectacles with a half-

1357
01:15:19,845 --> 01:15:24,516
moon cut in ’em,” resumed the narrator,
“and he carried a tin box strung to a

1358
01:15:24,516 --> 01:15:30,128
strap I took for his lunch till it flew
open on him and a horn toad hustled out.

1359
01:15:30,128 --> 01:15:34,537
Then I was sure he was a botanist⁠—or
whatever yu’ say they’re called.

1360
01:15:34,537 --> 01:15:39,542
Well, he would have owl eggs⁠—them little
prairie-owl that some claim can turn

1361
01:15:39,542 --> 01:15:44,306
their head clean around and keep a-
watchin’ yu’, only that’s nonsense.

1362
01:15:44,306 --> 01:15:48,197
We was ridin’ through that prairie-dog
town, used to be on the flat just after

1363
01:15:48,197 --> 01:15:51,568
yu’ crossed the south fork of Powder
River on the Buffalo trail,

1364
01:15:51,568 --> 01:15:55,399
and I said I’d dig an owl nest out for
him if he was willing to camp

1365
01:15:55,399 --> 01:15:56,209
till I’d dug it.

1366
01:15:56,209 --> 01:16:01,600
I wanted to know about them owls some
myself⁠—if they did live with the dogs

1367
01:16:01,600 --> 01:16:05,236
and snakes, yu’ know,”
he broke off, appealing to me.

1368
01:16:05,236 --> 01:16:07,263
“Oh, yes,” I told him eagerly.

1369
01:16:07,263 --> 01:16:12,605
“So while the botanist went glarin’
around the town with his glasses to see

1370
01:16:12,605 --> 01:16:16,845
if he could spot a prairie-dog and an
owl usin’ the same hole,

1371
01:16:16,845 --> 01:16:19,525
I was diggin’ in a hole I’d seen
an owl run down.

1372
01:16:19,525 --> 01:16:21,204
And that’s what I got.”

1373
01:16:21,204 --> 01:16:22,924
He held up his thumb again.

1374
01:16:22,924 --> 01:16:23,905
“The snake!”

1375
01:16:23,905 --> 01:16:24,977
I exclaimed.

1376
01:16:24,977 --> 01:16:25,983
“Yes, sir.

1377
01:16:25,983 --> 01:16:26,385
Mr.

1378
01:16:26,385 --> 01:16:29,105
Rattler was keepin’ house that day.

1379
01:16:29,105 --> 01:16:30,666
Took me right there.

1380
01:16:30,666 --> 01:16:34,085
I hauled him out of the
hole hangin’ to me.

1381
01:16:34,085 --> -1:59:59,000
Eight rattles.

1382
-1:59:59,000 --> 00:00:02,000
”

1383
01:16:37,049 --> 01:16:37,477
“Eight!”

1384
01:16:37,477 --> 01:16:38,488
said I.

1385
01:16:38,488 --> -1:59:59,000
“A big one.

1386
-1:59:59,000 --> 00:00:02,000
”

1387
01:16:40,238 --> 01:16:43,481
“Yes, sir.

1388
01:16:43,481 --> 01:16:45,357
Thought I was dead.

1389
01:16:45,357 --> 01:16:46,779
But the woman⁠—”

1390
01:16:46,779 --> 01:16:47,530
“The woman?”

1391
01:16:47,530 --> 01:16:48,237
said I.

