1889
01:40:17,160 --> 01:40:18,818
“That’s so,” said the native.

1890
01:40:18,818 --> 01:40:20,138
“And it paid good?”

1891
01:40:20,138 --> 01:40:23,102
“The only money in the county was right
there,” answered the Virginian.

1892
01:40:23,102 --> 01:40:27,959
“It was a dead county,
and only frawgs was movin’.

1893
01:40:27,959 --> 01:40:31,599
But that business was a-fannin’ to beat
four of a kind.

1894
01:40:31,599 --> 01:40:35,020
It made yu’ feel strange at
first, as I said.

1895
01:40:35,020 --> 01:40:38,577
For all the men had been cattlemen at
one time or another.

1896
01:40:38,577 --> 01:40:42,165
Till yu’ got accustomed,
it would give ’most anybody a shock to

1897
01:40:42,165 --> 01:40:45,591
hear ’em speak about herdin’ the bulls
in a pasture by themselves.”

1898
01:40:45,591 --> 01:40:50,191
The Virginian allowed himself another
smile, but became serious again.

1899
01:40:50,191 --> 01:40:53,652
“That was their policy,” he explained.

1900
01:40:53,652 --> 01:40:58,973
“Except at certain times o’ year they
kept the bulls separate.

1901
01:40:58,973 --> 01:41:01,956
The Fish Commission told ’em they’d
better, and it cert’nly

1902
01:41:01,956 --> 01:41:03,328
worked mighty well.

1903
01:41:03,328 --> 01:41:06,833
It or something did⁠—for, gentlemen, hush!

1904
01:41:06,833 --> 01:41:08,979
but there was millions.

1905
01:41:08,979 --> 01:41:14,539
You’d have said all the frawgs in the
world had taken charge at Tulare.

1906
01:41:14,539 --> 01:41:16,601
And the money rolled in!

1907
01:41:16,601 --> 01:41:18,323
Gentlemen, hush!

1908
01:41:18,323 --> 01:41:20,853
’twas a gold mine for the owners.

1909
01:41:20,853 --> 01:41:24,435
